{"title_page": "Samuel Herschel Schulman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Samuel Herschel Schulman\n| image              = Sammy-4.jpg\n| caption            = Sam Schulman at Virginia Holocaust Museum, 2003\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1928|7|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Terre Haute, Indiana]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2019|7|5|1928|7|8}}\n| death_place        = Richmond, Virginia, U.S.\n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| other_names        = Sam Schulman\n| occupation         = Seaman, Watchmaker/Jeweler\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = Crew member on the Aliya Bet ship 'Exodus 47'; early founder of Kibbutz Mishmar HaNegev; veteran of Israel's War of Independence\n| spouse             = \n| awards             = \n| website            = \n| signature          = \n}}\n'''Samuel Herschel Schulman''' (July 8, 1928 - July 5, 2019) was the last surviving American crew member of the celebrated ship ''[[Exodus 1947]],'' which attempted to bring thousands of Holocaust survivors from Europe to pre-state Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Born in Terra Haute, Indiana to Jewish immigrants from Poland, he moved to Paris in 1932, surviving the [[Holocaust]] in hiding in central France. \n\nAfter the war, he was repatriated to the United States where he joined the [[Aliya Bet]] and then fought in Israel's [[War of Independence]]. He returned to the United States in the 1950s and was drafted to the [[US Army]] during the [[Korean War]], serving two years training soldiers at [[Camp Edwards]] on Cape Cod, Massachusetts. After being released from the army, he went into jewelry business in New York City.\n\n== Early life ==\n\n=== Indiana ===\nSamuel Schulman was born in [[Terra Haute]], Indiana, on July 8, 1928. \n\nHis parents Hillel and Sarah Schulman (nee Sobkowska) immigrated to the United States from [[Warsaw]], Poland, in the 1920s. After his father died of appendicitis in 1932, he moved to Poland with his mother to be with her family. \n\nSarah Schulman remarried to an Orthodox rabbi, Moses Maidenbaum, and moved to [[Paris]], France, in 1933.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\n[[File:Teenager living in hiding in southern France.jpg|thumb|Sam Schulman as a teenager in Pionnat, France, 1944.]]\nIn May 1940, Germany invaded France and [[Paris in World War II|occupied Paris]] the following month. Sarah Schulman and her son had to register as Jews in order to obtain ration cards; she had to wear a Jewish star, but Sam Schulman, an American citizen, was exempt. Since Sarah Schulman was officially stateless, she could not return to the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1942, after the [[Gestapo]] conducted a round-up of Parisian Jews, Sam Schulman and his mother fled Paris. His step-father was on a business trip to the United States when the war broke out and could not return to France. \n\nSchulman and his mother were smuggled on a freight train to [[Limoges]], in the unoccupied zone, from where they continued to [[La Creuse]]. They remained in hiding in the small town of Pionnat, France, from 1942 to 1945.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Features/Paris-to-Pionnat|title=Paris to Pionnat|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=December 10, 2007|website=Jerusalem Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> While Schulman and his mother survived the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], most of his family in Poland, including his grandmother, aunts and uncles, perished in [[Auschwitz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1946, Schulman and his mother were repatriated to United States through the [[Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society]] (HIAS).\n\n== Exodus and the Aliya Bet ==\n[[File:Dad Exodus47a.png|thumb|Sam Schulman aboard the SS Exodus, 1947.]]\n[[File:Exodus 1947 after British takeover.jpg|thumb|SS Exodus '47]]\nIn March 1947, Schulman was instructed by a contact in the [[Haganah]] in New York to go to [[Baltimore]], Maryland, where he thought he would board a ship as a passenger to [[British Mandate-Palestine|British-mandate Palestine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> When he got to the Baltimore Harbor on March 23, 1947, he learned that he was to become part of the [[Mossad LeAliyah Bet]] and serve as a crew member aboard the famed illegal refugee ship ''[[SS Exodus|Exodus 1947]]''. \n\nThe ''Exodus 1947'' left [[S\u00e8te]], France on July 11, 1947, with 4,515 Jewish refugees<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hochstein|first=Joseph|title=The Jews' Secret Fleet|publisher=Gefen|year=1987|isbn=965-229-023-8|location=Jerusalem|pages=}}</ref>. [[Ike Aronowicz]] was the ship's captain and the [[Haganah]] commander of the operation was [[Yossi Harel]]. The ship was manned by a crew of some 35 volunteers, mostly American Jews, including Samuel Schulman.\n\nSchulman also sailed on two other [[Aliyah Bet|Aliya Bet]] ships, the ''Pan Crescent'' and ''Pan York'', which left from the port of Burgas, Bulgaria, on December 27, 1947 with over 15,000 immigrants.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hochstein|first=Joseph|title=The Jews' Secret Fleet|publisher=Gefen|year=1987|isbn=965-229-023-8|location=Jerusalem|pages=}}</ref> Several days later they were stopped by British warships and forced to anchor at [[Famagusta]], Cyprus. \n\nAbout his experience on the ships, Schulman once said: <blockquote>''\u201cThe Exodus might have been the most famous of all the Aliya Bet ships, but the Pan ships brought the largest number of refugees from Europe at one time.\u201d'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.larchmontgazette.com/2003/features/20030802schulman.html|title=Larchmont Ex-Prisoner Returns to Famagusta|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=August 7, 2003|website=Larchmont Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> </blockquote>Schulman spent six weeks in a British internment camp on [[Cyprus]] before being smuggled out by the [[Haganah]] in January 1948 on the Jewish passenger liner the ''Kedmah'' under the alias of one of the immigrants approved by the monthly British quota to [[Mandatory Palestine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe ''Exodus'' was popularized in the 1958 bestseller of the same name by [[Leon Uris]], and later made into a Hollywood film based on the book starring [[Paul Newman]].\n\n== Israel ==\nArriving in the port of Haifa in January 1948, Schulman headed south to help settle Kibbutz [[Mishmar HaNegev]] with friends he knew from his youth movement days in France. \n\nHe would then fight in Israel\u2019s War of Independence, training seamen in navigation at a naval base in Haifa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1987, Schulman and other [[Aliyah Bet|Aliya Bet]] volunteers were honored by Israeli President [[Chaim Herzog]] for their contributions to the [[Israel|State of Israel]]. At this first reunion of the American volunteers in Jerusalem, Herzog said:<blockquote>''\"Out of six million American Jews, it was you who jumped into the breach.''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israel.org/MFA/MFA-Archive/1999/Pages/FOCUS%20on%20Israel-%20MACHAL%20-%20Overseas%20Volunteers.aspx|title=MACHAL - Overseas Volunteers|last=|first=|date=May 1999|website=Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>In a letter to mark the occasion, then-Minister of Defense, [[Yitzhak Rabin]], wrote:<blockquote>''\"Your participation in the struggle of the Jewish People to bring the Holocaust survivors to Eretz Israel will be inscribed in the history of the People of Israel as a bright chapter of volunteering spirit and as a meaningful contribution to the establishment of Israel.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.machal.org.il/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=585&Itemid=953&lang=en|title=Letter from Yitzhak Rabin to the Aliyah Bet Reunion in Israel|last=Rabin|first=Yitzhak|date=February 23, 1987|website=World Machal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>In November 2018, Schulman received a medal and certificate from Israeli Minister of Jerusalem and Heritage Affairs, [[Ze'ev Elkin]], for his contribution to bringing Jewish immigrants to [[pre-state Israel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.israelhayom.com/2018/11/29/aliyah-bet-illegal-immigrants-to-israel-to-receive-medal-of-honor/|title=Aliyah Bet 'illegal' immigrants to Israel to receive medal of honor|last=Lavie|first=Dan|date=November 29, 2018|website=Israel Hayom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== United States ==\nShortly after his return to the United States from Israel in 1949, Schulman was drafted to the [[Korean War]]. He spent two years training soldiers at [[Camp Edwards]] on Cape Cod, Massachusetts, rising to the rank of Sergeant First Class.\n\nAfter the war, Schulman studied at Brooklyn College and then at the Joseph Bulova School of Watchmaking in Queens, NY, on the [[GI Bill]]. He went on to set up a watchmaking business in the diamond exchange district on Canal Street and the Bowery in lower Manhattan where he worked for 40 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSam Schulman married Eileen Azif of Mt. Vernon, New York in 1964 and have two sons. His daughter-in-law is [https://embassies.gov.il/un/AboutTheEmbassy/Pages/Ambassador%20Noa%20Furman.aspx Noa Furman], Deputy Permanent Representative of Israel to the [[United Nations]]. \n\nA long-time resident of [[Larchmont, New York|Larchmont]], New York, Sam Schulman moved to [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], Virginia in 2014. He passed away a few days before his 91st birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>  \n\n== References ==\n[[Category:The Holocaust]]\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Uris, Leon 1958, ''Exodus'' Doubleday Press, Chapter 27 specific to the Exodus true story.\n* Gruber, Ruth, 1999. ''Exodus 1947: the ship that launched a nation''. New York: Times Books. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Special:BookSources/0-8129-3154-8|0-8129-3154-8]]. OCLC 4095423\n* Hochstein, Joseph M.; Murray Greenfield. ''The Jews' Secret Fleet''. Jerusalem: Gefen. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Special:BookSources/965-229-023-8|965-229-023-8]]. OCLC 19030133\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.exodus1947.com/ Exodus1947.com] PBS Documentary Film focusing on the secret American involvement, narrated by Morley Safer\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q1mQuh9dy30 Sam Schulman - Oklahoma] Toldot Yisrael YouTube video\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mvKyVDfqFkM Sam Schulman video interview] Virginia Holocaust Museum\n*[https://collections.ushmm.org/search/?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=samuel+Schulman&search_field=all_fields Selected Sam Schulman documents and photos] US Holocaust Memorial Museum\n\n[[Category:World War II]]\n[[Category:Mandatory Palestine]]\n[[Category:Korean War]]\n[[Category:France]]\n[[Category:Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Samuel Herschel Schulman\n| image              = Sammy-4.jpg\n| caption            = Sam Schulman at Virginia Holocaust Museum, 2003\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1928|7|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Terre Haute, Indiana]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2019|7|5|1928|7|8}}\n| death_place        = Richmond, Virginia, U.S.\n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| other_names        = Sam Schulman\n| occupation         = Seaman, Watchmaker/Jeweler\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = Crew member on the Aliya Bet ship 'Exodus 47'; early founder of Kibbutz Mishmar HaNegev; veteran of Israel's War of Independence\n| spouse             = \n| awards             = \n| website            = \n| signature          = \n}}\n'''Samuel Herschel Schulman''' (July 8, 1928 - July 5, 2019) was the last surviving American crew member of the celebrated ship ''[[Exodus 1947]],'' which attempted to bring thousands of Holocaust survivors from Europe to pre-state Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Born in Terra Haute, Indiana to Jewish immigrants from Poland, he moved to Paris in 1932, surviving the [[Holocaust]] in hiding in central France. \n\nAfter the war, he was repatriated to the United States where he joined the [[Aliya Bet]] and then fought in Israel's [[War of Independence]]. He returned to the United States in the 1950s and was drafted to the [[US Army]] during the [[Korean War]], serving two years training soldiers at [[Camp Edwards]] on Cape Cod, Massachusetts. After being released from the army, he went into jewelry business in New York City.\n\n== Early life ==\n\n=== Indiana ===\nSamuel Schulman was born in [[Terra Haute]], Indiana, on July 8, 1928. \n\nHis parents Hillel and Sarah Schulman (nee Sobkowska) immigrated to the United States from [[Warsaw]], Poland, in the 1920s. After his father died of appendicitis in 1932, he moved to Poland with his mother to be with her family. \n\nSarah Schulman remarried to an Orthodox rabbi, Moses Maidenbaum, and moved to [[Paris]], France, in 1933.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\n[[File:Teenager living in hiding in southern France.jpg|thumb|Sam Schulman as a teenager in Pionnat, France, 1944.]]\nIn May 1940, Germany invaded France and [[Paris in World War II|occupied Paris]] the following month. Sarah Schulman and her son had to register as Jews in order to obtain ration cards; she had to wear a Jewish star, but Sam Schulman, an American citizen, was exempt. Since Sarah Schulman was officially stateless, she could not return to the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1942, after the [[Gestapo]] conducted a round-up of Parisian Jews, Sam Schulman and his mother fled Paris. His step-father was on a business trip to the United States when the war broke out and could not return to France. \n\nSchulman and his mother were smuggled on a freight train to [[Limoges]], in the unoccupied zone, from where they continued to [[La Creuse]]. They remained in hiding in the small town of Pionnat, France, from 1942 to 1945.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Features/Paris-to-Pionnat|title=Paris to Pionnat|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=December 10, 2007|website=Jerusalem Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> While Schulman and his mother survived the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], most of his family in Poland, including his grandmother, aunts and uncles, perished in [[Auschwitz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1946, Schulman and his mother were repatriated to United States through the [[Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society]] (HIAS).\n\n== Exodus and the Aliya Bet ==\n[[File:Dad Exodus47a.png|thumb|Sam Schulman aboard the SS Exodus, 1947.]]\n[[File:Exodus 1947 after British takeover.jpg|thumb|SS Exodus '47]]\nIn March 1947, Schulman was instructed by a contact in the [[Haganah]] in New York to go to [[Baltimore]], Maryland, where he thought he would board a ship as a passenger to [[British Mandate-Palestine|British-mandate Palestine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> When he got to the Baltimore Harbor on March 23, 1947, he learned that he was to become part of the [[Mossad LeAliyah Bet]] and serve as a crew member aboard the famed illegal refugee ship ''[[SS Exodus|Exodus 1947]]''. \n\nThe ''Exodus 1947'' left [[S\u00e8te]], France on July 11, 1947, with 4,515 Jewish refugees<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hochstein|first=Joseph|title=The Jews' Secret Fleet|publisher=Gefen|year=1987|isbn=965-229-023-8|location=Jerusalem|pages=}}</ref>. [[Ike Aronowicz]] was the ship's captain and the [[Haganah]] commander of the operation was [[Yossi Harel]]. The ship was manned by a crew of some 35 volunteers, mostly American Jews, including Samuel Schulman.\n\nSchulman also sailed on two other [[Aliyah Bet|Aliya Bet]] ships, the ''Pan Crescent'' and ''Pan York'', which left from the port of Burgas, Bulgaria, on December 27, 1947 with over 15,000 immigrants.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hochstein|first=Joseph|title=The Jews' Secret Fleet|publisher=Gefen|year=1987|isbn=965-229-023-8|location=Jerusalem|pages=}}</ref> Several days later they were stopped by British warships and forced to anchor at [[Famagusta]], Cyprus. \n\nAbout his experience on the ships, Schulman once said: <blockquote>''\u201cThe Exodus might have been the most famous of all the Aliya Bet ships, but the Pan ships brought the largest number of refugees from Europe at one time.\u201d'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.larchmontgazette.com/2003/features/20030802schulman.html|title=Larchmont Ex-Prisoner Returns to Famagusta|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=August 7, 2003|website=Larchmont Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> </blockquote>Schulman spent six weeks in a British internment camp on [[Cyprus]] before being smuggled out by the [[Haganah]] in January 1948 on the Jewish passenger liner the ''Kedmah'' under the alias of one of the immigrants approved by the monthly British quota to [[Mandatory Palestine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe ''Exodus'' was popularized in the 1958 bestseller of the same name by [[Leon Uris]], and later made into a Hollywood film based on the book starring [[Paul Newman]].\n\n== Israel ==\nArriving in the port of Haifa in January 1948, Schulman headed south to help settle Kibbutz [[Mishmar HaNegev]] with friends he knew from his youth movement days in France. \n\nHe would then fight in Israel\u2019s War of Independence, training seamen in navigation at a naval base in Haifa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1987, Schulman and other [[Aliyah Bet|Aliya Bet]] volunteers were honored by Israeli President [[Chaim Herzog]] for their contributions to the [[Israel|State of Israel]]. At this first reunion of the American volunteers in Jerusalem, Herzog said:<blockquote>''\"Out of six million American Jews, it was you who jumped into the breach.''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israel.org/MFA/MFA-Archive/1999/Pages/FOCUS%20on%20Israel-%20MACHAL%20-%20Overseas%20Volunteers.aspx|title=MACHAL - Overseas Volunteers|last=|first=|date=May 1999|website=Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>In a letter to mark the occasion, then-Minister of Defense, [[Yitzhak Rabin]], wrote:<blockquote>''\"Your participation in the struggle of the Jewish People to bring the Holocaust survivors to Eretz Israel will be inscribed in the history of the People of Israel as a bright chapter of volunteering spirit and as a meaningful contribution to the establishment of Israel.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.machal.org.il/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=585&Itemid=953&lang=en|title=Letter from Yitzhak Rabin to the Aliyah Bet Reunion in Israel|last=Rabin|first=Yitzhak|date=February 23, 1987|website=World Machal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>In November 2018, Schulman received a medal and certificate from Israeli Minister of Jerusalem and Heritage Affairs, [[Ze'ev Elkin]], for his contribution to bringing Jewish immigrants to [[pre-state Israel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.israelhayom.com/2018/11/29/aliyah-bet-illegal-immigrants-to-israel-to-receive-medal-of-honor/|title=Aliyah Bet 'illegal' immigrants to Israel to receive medal of honor|last=Lavie|first=Dan|date=November 29, 2018|website=Israel Hayom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== United States ==\nShortly after his return to the United States from Israel in 1949, Schulman was drafted to the [[Korean War]]. He spent two years training soldiers at [[Camp Edwards]] on Cape Cod, Massachusetts, rising to the rank of Sergeant First Class.\n\nAfter the war, Schulman studied at Brooklyn College and then at the Joseph Bulova School of Watchmaking in Queens, NY, on the [[GI Bill]]. He went on to set up a watchmaking business in the diamond exchange district on Canal Street and the Bowery in lower Manhattan where he worked for 40 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSam Schulman married Eileen Azif of Mt. Vernon, New York in 1964 and have two sons. His daughter-in-law is [https://embassies.gov.il/un/AboutTheEmbassy/Pages/Ambassador%20Noa%20Furman.aspx Noa Furman], Deputy Permanent Representative of Israel to the [[United Nations]]. \n\n== References ==\n[[Category:The Holocaust]]\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Uris, Leon 1958, ''Exodus'' Doubleday Press, Chapter 27 specific to the Exodus true story.\n* Gruber, Ruth, 1999. ''Exodus 1947: the ship that launched a nation''. New York: Times Books. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Special:BookSources/0-8129-3154-8|0-8129-3154-8]]. OCLC 4095423\n* Hochstein, Joseph M.; Murray Greenfield. ''The Jews' Secret Fleet''. Jerusalem: Gefen. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Special:BookSources/965-229-023-8|965-229-023-8]]. OCLC 19030133\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.exodus1947.com/ Exodus1947.com] PBS Documentary Film focusing on the secret American involvement, narrated by Morley Safer\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q1mQuh9dy30 Sam Schulman - Oklahoma] Toldot Yisrael YouTube video\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mvKyVDfqFkM Sam Schulman video interview] Virginia Holocaust Museum\n*[https://collections.ushmm.org/search/?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=samuel+Schulman&search_field=all_fields Selected Sam Schulman documents and photos] US Holocaust Memorial Museum\n\n[[Category:World War II]]\n[[Category:Mandatory Palestine]]\n[[Category:Korean War]]\n[[Category:France]]\n[[Category:Israel]]\n", "name_user": "Marknoa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited States:Added a line in personal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Herschel_Schulman"}
{"title_page": "Tej Bahadur Sapru", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian lawyer and politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n'''Sir Tej Bahadur Sapru''', [[Order of the Star of India|KCSI]], [[His Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] (8 December 1875{{Snd}} 20 January 1949) was a prominent [[India]]n freedom fighter, lawyer and politician. He was a key figure in India's struggle for independence, helping draft the [[Indian Constitution]]. He was the leader of the [[Indian Liberal Party|Liberal party]] in British-ruled India.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Early life and career==\nTej Bahadur Sapru was born in [[Aligarh]] in the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] (now [[Uttar Pradesh]]). He was born in a [[Kashmiri Pandit|Kashmiri]] [[Hindu]] family.<ref name=\"Mohan Kumar\">{{cite book|url =https://books.google.com/?id=b7u1AAAAIAAJ&q=Sapru+Kashmiri&dq=Sapru+Kashmiri|author=Mohan Kumar|title=Sir Tej Bahadur Sapru: a poli\ud83c\udf1dtical biography|publisher =Vipul Prakashan|quote= Even now there are many distinguished scholars of Persian among the Kashmiri Brahmins in India. Sir Tej Bahadur Sapru and Raja Narendranath to mention two of them.|accessdate = 2007-03-25|year=1981}}</ref> He was educated at the Agra College. Sapru worked in the [[Allahabad High Court]] as a [[lawyer]] where [[Purushottam Das Tandon]], a future nationalist leader, worked as his junior. He later served as a Dean of the [[Banaras Hindu University]]{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}. On 13 December 1930 Sapru was admitted to the [[Middle Temple]], but withdrew on 14 January 1932 without being [[Called to the Bar]].<ref>Sturgess, H.A.C. (1949). ''Register of Admissions to the Honourable Society of the Middle Temple''. Butterworth & Co. (Publishers) Ltd.: Temple Bar. Vol. 3, p.927.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nSapru served in the Legislative Council of the United Provinces (1913\u201316) and the Imperial Legislative Council (1916\u201320) and as a member for law affairs in the Viceroy's Council (1920\u201323). Sapru and Indian Liberals collaborated with the Congress after the ascent of [[Mahatma Gandhi]], who advocated [[Satyagraha|non-violent civil disobedience]] against British rule. Sapru supported the [[Non-cooperation movement]] until (1920\u201322).  He was knighted as a Knight Commander of the Order of the Star of India (KCSI) in the 1923 King's Birthday Honours list,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32782|supp=4|date=1 January 1923|page=4}}</ref> As early as 1927, Sapru organized an All Party Conference to begin drafting the [[Indian Constitution]]. In 1928, he helped draft the Nehru Committee Report on Constitutional Reforms. It is acknowledged as the most important document related to the evolution of the Indian Constitution. For the first time in the history of India, it proposed uniting the princely states with the rest of India as a part of the federal polity. \n\nAlthough initially a member of the [[Indian National Congress]], India's largest political party, Sapru left it to join the Liberal party of India. While he supported ''[[Swaraj]]'' (Self Rule) and [[civil disobedience]] against British colonial rule, as a constitutionalist, Sapru advocated for greater political rights and freedoms for Indians to be achieved through dialogue with British authorities. For example, on 28 February 1930, he attended a dinner party organised by the Standing Committee of British India and minister advisers.  [[Chimanlal Setalvad]] from Bombay was also present ready to co-operate with Muslims M A Jinnah, and [[M R Jayakar]], alongside C P Ramaswami Aiyer from Madras.  The Committee absorbed Haksar's Report, and agreed to hold monthly meetings; their deliberations became known as the Sapru Committee recommendations. These \"conversations with the princes are very important\" declared New Delhi.<ref>Setalvad to Sapru, 10 March 1930, National Library of India (NLI), Sapru MSS, I, 24, S 124; ed. B R Nanda, ''Essays in Modern Indian History,'' Delhi: OUP, 1980, p.123.</ref> [[Kailas Nath Haksar]] was a personal friend who also proposed federation of British and princely India, responsibility was a conservative counter-weight to radicalisation.  They established good relations with the British Ministry of Works and Gandhi to build a forum for the round table conference.  On 17 November 1930 the All-India Federation gained princely support for a constitutional relationship.  Although unaware of the impact of this shift, Sapru sought out Gandhi and Nehru for conversations against civil disobedience movements.  He was not successful, other than drawing criticism from Nehru about British control over the Army and financial safeguards.  However they had more success in Bhopal and Bikaner, proposed the establishment of a Centre Party with allies in Oudh and United Provinces.  They were in no stronger position when the Second Round Table Conference started.  The factional splits were fatal to the princes cause; and Sapru's severe criticisms of Maharaja of Dholpur only served to postpone federation.  But he persevered with colleagues Jayakar and Haksar to lobby officials, when he was informed the Viceroy warned against repudiation.  Lord Willingdon remained aloof and indifferent to his efforts.  The bureaucratic denials slowed attempts, and so in early 1932 Lord Lothian of the Franchise Committee made overtures towards Federation, they recruited Hailey's organ ''The Pioneer'' to persuade the princes to donate.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019|reason=Entire paragraph needs cites}}\n\nSapru and other Liberal politicians, eager to achieve independence through dialogue, participated in the central and provincial legislatures set up by the British, even though they were opposed by most Indian political parties and ignored by the people, who considered the legislatures to be unrepresentative \"rubber stamps\" for the [[Viceroy of India]].  Many Congress politicians respected Sapru as an eminent jurist, as he was a valuable and effective mediator. Sapru mediated between Gandhi and the Viceroy [[Lord Irwin]], helping to forge the [[Gandhi\u2013Irwin Pact]] that ended the Salt Satyagraha.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} Sapru also mediated between Gandhi, Dr. [[Bhimrao Ramji Ambedkar]] and the British over the issue of separate electorates for India's \"[[Harijan|Untouchables]]\", which was settled by the [[Poona Pact]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} Sapru was chosen as the representative of Indian Liberals at the [[Round Table Conferences (India)|Round Table Conferences]] (1931\u201333), which sought to deliberate plans over granting more autonomy to Indians. His efforts along with those of his contemporary [[M. R. Jayakar]] at the Round Table Conferences for bridging the differences between the British administration and Congress are well known.  But by Third Round Table many princes would not turn up, and their ministers were lukewarm about federation, and personalities clashed to exclude his able lieutenant Haksar. Sapru had to battle conservative intransigent and princely fickleness when participation was largely voluntary.<ref>''Report of the Joint Committee on Indian Constitutional Reform'' (session 1933-4), vol.1, pt.1 (London, 1934); Nanda, p.144.</ref>  He was appointed a member of the Privy Council on 26 February 1934.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34168|page=3691|date=7 June 1935}}</ref>\n\nSapru supported the Viceroy's decision to bring India into the Second World War in 1939, even as the Congress criticised the decision as unilateral and made without consulting the representatives of India's people. Sapru was also one of the main lawyers engaged to defend captured soldiers of the rebel [[Indian National Army]], raised by nationalist leader [[Subhas Chandra Bose]] with the aid of [[Imperial Japan]] during the war{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}and the [[Quit India Movement]] (1942\u201346).\n\n=== Sapru Committee Report ===\nIn 1944, the Standing Committee of the Non-Party Conference adopted a resolution to appoint a committee that would make recommendations on constitutional principles, taking into particular account issues of communal division in India. Sapru was invited to head the committee, and to appoint members representing various communities to participate in the preparation of its report.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.276348|title=Constitutional Proposals of the Sapru Committee|last=Sapru|first=Tej Bahadur  | display-authors = etal|publisher=Padma Publications|year=1945|isbn=|location=Bombay|pages=}}</ref> This report, titled 'Constitutional Proposals of the Sapru Committee', came to be commonly known as the Sapru Committee Report, and contained 21 recommendations pertaining to constitutional questions that concerned the governance and politics of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.constitutionofindia.net/historical_constitutions/sapru_committee_report__sir_tej_bahadur_sapru__1945__1st%20December%201945|title=Sapru Committee Report (Sir Tej Bahadur Sapru, 1945)|last=Center for Law and Policy Research|date=|website=CADIndia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>The Report was published along with a detailed exposition of the reasoning behind these recommendations and included a number of notes of dissent from committee members, as well as details of correspondence regarding their deliberations between the committee and political figures such as [[B. R. Ambedkar|B.R. Ambedkar]], [[Mahatma Gandhi|Gandhi]], and others.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Sapru Committee Report rejected the proposal for the division of the Indian sub-continent into the two states of India and Pakistan, and made a number of recommendations for the protection of minorities in a unified state.<ref name=\":0\" /> While the Report did not receive much attention or consideration when it was published, it was cited and considered a number of times by the [[Constituent Assembly of India]] when drafting the [[Constitution of India]].<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://164.100.47.194/Loksabha/Debates/cadebatefiles/C09121946.html|title=Constituent Assembly Of India Debates (Proceedings)|last=Constituent Assembly of India|publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat, Government of India|year=1946|isbn=|volume=I|location=New Delhi|pages=|chapter='Chairman's Inaugural Address'}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://164.100.47.194/Loksabha/Debates/cadebatefiles/C29071947.html|title=Constituent Assembly of India Debates (Proceedings)|last=Constituent Assembly of India|first=1956|publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat|year=|isbn=|volume=IV|location=New Delhi|pages=|chapter='Speech by M. Ananthasayanam Ayyangar (29 July 1947)'}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSapru was the only son of Ambika Prasad Sapru, a [[zemindar]], and his wife Gaura Sapru (n\u00e9e Hukku). Sapru's mother Gaura was the sister of Niranjan Hukku, whose daughter Uma was married to Shyamlal Nehru, a first cousin of [[Jawaharlal Nehru]]. Sapru was also an eighth cousin [[Allama Iqbal]], national poet of [[Pakistan]] and a Muslim ideologue who was among those who formulated the very idea of Pakistan in the 1930s. Allama Iqbal's grandfather was Sahaj Ram Sapru, a Hindu [[Kashmiri Brahmin]] who was a distant (but agnatic) relative of Sapru.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\nSapru and his wife were the parents of five children. Their three sons were Prakash Narain Sapru, Trijugi Narain Sapru, and Anand Narain Sapru and their daughters were named Jagdambashwari and Bhuvaneshwari. Sapru was the grandfather of [[Jagdish Narain Sapru]], former chairman of [[The BOC Group|British Oxygen]] and of [[ITC (company)|The ITC conglomerate]].{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\nSir Tej bahadur Sapru died on 20 January 1949 in [[Allahabad]], barely seventeen months after India gained independence.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*''Crusader for self-rule: Tej Bahadur Sapru & the Indian National Movement: life and selected letters''(1999) by Rima Hooja ASIN: B0006FEFZK,\n*''Tej Bahadur Sapru'' (Builders of modern India) by Sunil Kumar Bose, Publications Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Govt. of India (1978), ASIN: B0006E11GM\n*''Indian national movement and the liberals'' by Abha Saxena, Allahabad, India: Chugh Publications, 1986. foreword by A.C. Banerjee.\n*[http://www.houseofdavid.ca/Ind_uni.htm#Muldoon Muldoon, Andrew Robert, \"Making a `moderate' India: British conservatives, imperial culture and Indian political reform, 1924\u20131935\"]\n*[http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/stories/20090522261007900.htm Read this essay by A G Noorani to learn more about differences between Sapru and Mahatma Gandhi]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Indian National Army}}\n{{Indian independence movement}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sapru, Tej Bahadur}}\n[[Category:Indian National Army trials]]\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of British India]]\n[[Category:Indian socialists]]\n[[Category:Kashmiri people]]\n[[Category:People from Aligarh]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the Star of India]]\n[[Category:Indian knights]]\n[[Category:Members of the Imperial Legislative Council of India]]\n[[Category:Indian members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of Central Legislative Assembly of India]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian lawyers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian lawyer and politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n'''Sir Tej Bahadur Sapru''', [[Order of the Star of India|KCSI]], [[His Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] (8 December 1875{{Snd}} 20 January 1949) was a prominent [[India]]n freedom fighter, lawyer and politician. He was a key figure in India's struggle for independence, helping draft the [[Indian Constitution]]. He was the leader of the [[Indian Liberal Party|Liberal party]] in British-ruled India.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Early life and career==\nTej Bahadur Sapru was born in [[Aligarh]] in the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] (now [[Uttar Pradesh]]). He was born in a [[Kashmiri Pandit|Kashmiri]] [[Hindu]] family.<ref name=\"Mohan Kumar\">{{cite book|url =https://books.google.com/?id=b7u1AAAAIAAJ&q=Sapru+Kashmiri&dq=Sapru+Kashmiri|author=Mohan Kumar|title=Sir Tej Bahadur Sapru: a political biography|publisher =Vipul Prakashan|quote= Even now there are many distinguished scholars of Persian among the Kashmiri Brahmins in India. Sir Tej Bahadur Sapru and Raja Narendranath to mention two of them.|accessdate = 2007-03-25|year=1981}}</ref> He was educated at the Agra College. Sapru worked in the [[Allahabad High Court]] as a [[lawyer]] where [[Purushottam Das Tandon]], a future nationalist leader, worked as his junior. He later served as a Dean of the [[Banaras Hindu University]]{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}. On 13 December 1930 Sapru was admitted to the [[Middle Temple]], but withdrew on 14 January 1932 without being [[Called to the Bar]].<ref>Sturgess, H.A.C. (1949). ''Register of Admissions to the Honourable Society of the Middle Temple''. Butterworth & Co. (Publishers) Ltd.: Temple Bar. Vol. 3, p.927.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nSapru served in the Legislative Council of the United Provinces (1913\u201316) and the Imperial Legislative Council (1916\u201320) and as a member for law affairs in the Viceroy's Council (1920\u201323). Sapru and Indian Liberals collaborated with the Congress after the ascent of [[Mahatma Gandhi]], who advocated [[Satyagraha|non-violent civil disobedience]] against British rule. Sapru supported the [[Non-cooperation movement]] until (1920\u201322).  He was knighted as a Knight Commander of the Order of the Star of India (KCSI) in the 1923 King's Birthday Honours list,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32782|supp=4|date=1 January 1923|page=4}}</ref> As early as 1927, Sapru organized an All Party Conference to begin drafting the [[Indian Constitution]]. In 1928, he helped draft the Nehru Committee Report on Constitutional Reforms. It is acknowledged as the most important document related to the evolution of the Indian Constitution. For the first time in the history of India, it proposed uniting the princely states with the rest of India as a part of the federal polity. \n\nAlthough initially a member of the [[Indian National Congress]], India's largest political party, Sapru left it to join the Liberal party of India. While he supported ''[[Swaraj]]'' (Self Rule) and [[civil disobedience]] against British colonial rule, as a constitutionalist, Sapru advocated for greater political rights and freedoms for Indians to be achieved through dialogue with British authorities. For example, on 28 February 1930, he attended a dinner party organised by the Standing Committee of British India and minister advisers.  [[Chimanlal Setalvad]] from Bombay was also present ready to co-operate with Muslims M A Jinnah, and [[M R Jayakar]], alongside C P Ramaswami Aiyer from Madras.  The Committee absorbed Haksar's Report, and agreed to hold monthly meetings; their deliberations became known as the Sapru Committee recommendations. These \"conversations with the princes are very important\" declared New Delhi.<ref>Setalvad to Sapru, 10 March 1930, National Library of India (NLI), Sapru MSS, I, 24, S 124; ed. B R Nanda, ''Essays in Modern Indian History,'' Delhi: OUP, 1980, p.123.</ref> [[Kailas Nath Haksar]] was a personal friend who also proposed federation of British and princely India, responsibility was a conservative counter-weight to radicalisation.  They established good relations with the British Ministry of Works and Gandhi to build a forum for the round table conference.  On 17 November 1930 the All-India Federation gained princely support for a constitutional relationship.  Although unaware of the impact of this shift, Sapru sought out Gandhi and Nehru for conversations against civil disobedience movements.  He was not successful, other than drawing criticism from Nehru about British control over the Army and financial safeguards.  However they had more success in Bhopal and Bikaner, proposed the establishment of a Centre Party with allies in Oudh and United Provinces.  They were in no stronger position when the Second Round Table Conference started.  The factional splits were fatal to the princes cause; and Sapru's severe criticisms of Maharaja of Dholpur only served to postpone federation.  But he persevered with colleagues Jayakar and Haksar to lobby officials, when he was informed the Viceroy warned against repudiation.  Lord Willingdon remained aloof and indifferent to his efforts.  The bureaucratic denials slowed attempts, and so in early 1932 Lord Lothian of the Franchise Committee made overtures towards Federation, they recruited Hailey's organ ''The Pioneer'' to persuade the princes to donate.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019|reason=Entire paragraph needs cites}}\n\nSapru and other Liberal politicians, eager to achieve independence through dialogue, participated in the central and provincial legislatures set up by the British, even though they were opposed by most Indian political parties and ignored by the people, who considered the legislatures to be unrepresentative \"rubber stamps\" for the [[Viceroy of India]].  Many Congress politicians respected Sapru as an eminent jurist, as he was a valuable and effective mediator. Sapru mediated between Gandhi and the Viceroy [[Lord Irwin]], helping to forge the [[Gandhi\u2013Irwin Pact]] that ended the Salt Satyagraha.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} Sapru also mediated between Gandhi, Dr. [[Bhimrao Ramji Ambedkar]] and the British over the issue of separate electorates for India's \"[[Harijan|Untouchables]]\", which was settled by the [[Poona Pact]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} Sapru was chosen as the representative of Indian Liberals at the [[Round Table Conferences (India)|Round Table Conferences]] (1931\u201333), which sought to deliberate plans over granting more autonomy to Indians. His efforts along with those of his contemporary [[M. R. Jayakar]] at the Round Table Conferences for bridging the differences between the British administration and Congress are well known.  But by Third Round Table many princes would not turn up, and their ministers were lukewarm about federation, and personalities clashed to exclude his able lieutenant Haksar. Sapru had to battle conservative intransigent and princely fickleness when participation was largely voluntary.<ref>''Report of the Joint Committee on Indian Constitutional Reform'' (session 1933-4), vol.1, pt.1 (London, 1934); Nanda, p.144.</ref>  He was appointed a member of the Privy Council on 26 February 1934.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34168|page=3691|date=7 June 1935}}</ref>\n\nSapru supported the Viceroy's decision to bring India into the Second World War in 1939, even as the Congress criticised the decision as unilateral and made without consulting the representatives of India's people. Sapru was also one of the main lawyers engaged to defend captured soldiers of the rebel [[Indian National Army]], raised by nationalist leader [[Subhas Chandra Bose]] with the aid of [[Imperial Japan]] during the war{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}and the [[Quit India Movement]] (1942\u201346).\n\n=== Sapru Committee Report ===\nIn 1944, the Standing Committee of the Non-Party Conference adopted a resolution to appoint a committee that would make recommendations on constitutional principles, taking into particular account issues of communal division in India. Sapru was invited to head the committee, and to appoint members representing various communities to participate in the preparation of its report.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.276348|title=Constitutional Proposals of the Sapru Committee|last=Sapru|first=Tej Bahadur  | display-authors = etal|publisher=Padma Publications|year=1945|isbn=|location=Bombay|pages=}}</ref> This report, titled 'Constitutional Proposals of the Sapru Committee', came to be commonly known as the Sapru Committee Report, and contained 21 recommendations pertaining to constitutional questions that concerned the governance and politics of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.constitutionofindia.net/historical_constitutions/sapru_committee_report__sir_tej_bahadur_sapru__1945__1st%20December%201945|title=Sapru Committee Report (Sir Tej Bahadur Sapru, 1945)|last=Center for Law and Policy Research|date=|website=CADIndia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>The Report was published along with a detailed exposition of the reasoning behind these recommendations and included a number of notes of dissent from committee members, as well as details of correspondence regarding their deliberations between the committee and political figures such as [[B. R. Ambedkar|B.R. Ambedkar]], [[Mahatma Gandhi|Gandhi]], and others.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Sapru Committee Report rejected the proposal for the division of the Indian sub-continent into the two states of India and Pakistan, and made a number of recommendations for the protection of minorities in a unified state.<ref name=\":0\" /> While the Report did not receive much attention or consideration when it was published, it was cited and considered a number of times by the [[Constituent Assembly of India]] when drafting the [[Constitution of India]].<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://164.100.47.194/Loksabha/Debates/cadebatefiles/C09121946.html|title=Constituent Assembly Of India Debates (Proceedings)|last=Constituent Assembly of India|publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat, Government of India|year=1946|isbn=|volume=I|location=New Delhi|pages=|chapter='Chairman's Inaugural Address'}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://164.100.47.194/Loksabha/Debates/cadebatefiles/C29071947.html|title=Constituent Assembly of India Debates (Proceedings)|last=Constituent Assembly of India|first=1956|publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat|year=|isbn=|volume=IV|location=New Delhi|pages=|chapter='Speech by M. Ananthasayanam Ayyangar (29 July 1947)'}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSapru was the only son of Ambika Prasad Sapru, a [[zemindar]], and his wife Gaura Sapru (n\u00e9e Hukku). Sapru's mother Gaura was the sister of Niranjan Hukku, whose daughter Uma was married to Shyamlal Nehru, a first cousin of [[Jawaharlal Nehru]]. Sapru was also an eighth cousin [[Allama Iqbal]], national poet of [[Pakistan]] and a Muslim ideologue who was among those who formulated the very idea of Pakistan in the 1930s. Allama Iqbal's grandfather was Sahaj Ram Sapru, a Hindu [[Kashmiri Brahmin]] who was a distant (but agnatic) relative of Sapru.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\nSapru and his wife were the parents of five children. Their three sons were Prakash Narain Sapru, Trijugi Narain Sapru, and Anand Narain Sapru and their daughters were named Jagdambashwari and Bhuvaneshwari. Sapru was the grandfather of [[Jagdish Narain Sapru]], former chairman of [[The BOC Group|British Oxygen]] and of [[ITC (company)|The ITC conglomerate]].{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\nSir Tej bahadur Sapru died on 20 January 1949 in [[Allahabad]], barely seventeen months after India gained independence.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*''Crusader for self-rule: Tej Bahadur Sapru & the Indian National Movement: life and selected letters''(1999) by Rima Hooja ASIN: B0006FEFZK,\n*''Tej Bahadur Sapru'' (Builders of modern India) by Sunil Kumar Bose, Publications Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Govt. of India (1978), ASIN: B0006E11GM\n*''Indian national movement and the liberals'' by Abha Saxena, Allahabad, India: Chugh Publications, 1986. foreword by A.C. Banerjee.\n*[http://www.houseofdavid.ca/Ind_uni.htm#Muldoon Muldoon, Andrew Robert, \"Making a `moderate' India: British conservatives, imperial culture and Indian political reform, 1924\u20131935\"]\n*[http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/stories/20090522261007900.htm Read this essay by A G Noorani to learn more about differences between Sapru and Mahatma Gandhi]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Indian National Army}}\n{{Indian independence movement}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sapru, Tej Bahadur}}\n[[Category:Indian National Army trials]]\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of British India]]\n[[Category:Indian socialists]]\n[[Category:Kashmiri people]]\n[[Category:People from Aligarh]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the Star of India]]\n[[Category:Indian knights]]\n[[Category:Members of the Imperial Legislative Council of India]]\n[[Category:Indian members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of Central Legislative Assembly of India]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian lawyers]]\n", "name_user": "2405:205:2300:a11e:1536:e797:5b01:7fa1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life and career:Nice)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tej_Bahadur_Sapru"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Kresna Gorge", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Kresna Gorge \n|partof=[[Second Balkan War]]   \n|image=  Greek advance Kresna 1913.jpg\n|image_size=  240px\n|caption=Greek units advancing in Kresna Gorge\n|date={{OldStyleDate|July, 21\u201331|1913|July, 8\u201318}}\n|place=[[Kresna Gorge]], [[Bulgaria]]  \n|result=Stalemate brought about by truce\n|combatant1=[[File:Flag of Bulgaria.svg|border|22px]] [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]]  \n|combatant2=[[File:Flag of Greece (1828-1978).svg|22px]] [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]]   \n|commander1=Gen. [[Mihail Savov]] <br> Gen. [[Nikola Ivanov]]\n|commander2=King [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine I]] \n|strength1=110 battalions{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n|strength2=80 battalions{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=10,000<ref>Cassavetti, D. J. ''Hellas and the Balkan wars.'' T. Fisher Unwin, London 1914. \u0440. 334</ref>\n}}   \n{{Campaignbox Second Balkan War}}\nThe '''Battle of Kresna Gorge''' was fought in 1913 between the [[Greeks]] and the [[Bulgarians]] during the [[Second Balkan War]]. It marked the last phase of the Greek advance into Bulgarian territory before the ceasefire and the following peace treaty.\n\n==Background==\nAfter the Serbian front became static, and seeing that the Bulgarian Army in his front had already suffered defeat, [[Constantine I of Greece|King Constantine]] ordered the Greek Army to march further into Bulgarian territory and take the capital city of [[Sofia]]. \n[[Constantine I of Greece|King Constantine]] wanted a decisive victory on this war despite the objections of Prime Minister [[Eleftherios Venizelos]] who realized that the Serbs, having won their territorial objectives, were now trying to move the weight of the rest of the war to the Greeks by staying passive. The battle was continued for eleven days, between July 8\u201318, over a front of 20&nbsp;km, in a maze of forests and mountains.\n\n==Conflict==\n\n===Greek advance and breaking through the Kresna pass ===\nAfter the victorious [[Battle of Doiran (1913)|Battle of Doiran]] the Greek forces continued their penetration north. On July 18, the [[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st Greek Division]], managed to drive back the Bulgarian rear guard and captured an important foothold at the southern end of the Kresna pass.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hellenic Army General Staff, Army History Directorate. [Ed. committee: Dimitrios Gedeon|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=9789607897077|pages=254|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ci9pAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>\n\nIn the pass, the Greeks were ambushed by the Bulgarian 2nd and 4th Armies which was newly arrived from the Serbian front and had taken up defensive positions there. However, after bitter fighting the Greek side managed to break through the Kresna pass. The Greek advance continued and on July 25, the village of Krupnik, north of the pass, was captured, forcing the Bulgarian troops to withdraw to [[Simitli]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=257|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n4-RAAAAIAAJ|edition=1.udg.}}</ref> Simitli was also captured on July 26,<ref>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=259|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ci9pAAAAMAAJ|edition=1.udg.}}</ref> while at the night of July 27\u201328 the Bulgarian forces were pushed north to Gorna Dzhumaya ([[Blagoevgrad]]), 76&nbsp;km south of [[Sofia]].<ref name=Gedeon260>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=260|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n4-RAAAAIAAJ|edition=1.udg.}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the Greek forces continued their march inland into western Thrace and on July 26, entered [[Xanthi]] and the next day entered [[Komotini]], without facing opposition.<ref name=Gedeon260/>\n\n===Bulgarian counterattack and armistice===\n[[File:Map Battle Simitli 1079 1378.jpeg|thumbnail|left|Advance of the Greek forces after breaking through the Kresna Gorge (July, 25\u201330)]]\nThe Greek army was stopped in front of Gorna Dzhumaya by significant Bulgarian resistance.<ref>History of the Bulgarians: The Military history of the Bulgarians from Ancient times until present day, Georgi Bakalov, 2007, [https://books.google.com/books?id=HDQn3tJkyUcC&pg=PA450 p.450], {{in lang|bg}}</ref><ref>Historical overview, Volume 38, Issues 4\u20136, 1982, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eBNpAAAAMAAJ p.112] {{in lang|bg}}</ref> In July 28, the Greek forces resumed the attack and captured a line stretching from Cherovo to Hill 1378, southeast of Gorna Dzhumaya.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hellenic Army General Staff, Army History Directorate. [Ed. committee: Dimitrios Gedeon|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=9789607897077|pages=261|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n4-RAAAAIAAJ|edition=1.udg.}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on the evening of July 28, under heavy pressure, the Bulgarian army was forced to abandon the town, while it set fire to a quarter of it during the retreat.<ref>Price, Crawfurd (1914). The Balkan cockpit. T. Werner Laurie LTD, p. 336</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Great Military and Naval Encyclopedia|year=1929|publisher=\u0388\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u039d\u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0395\u03b3\u03ba\u03c5\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|location=Athens|pages=300|accessdate=2 July 2012|language=Greek|volume=6|url=http://anemi.lib.uoc.gr/metadata/e/3/e/metadata-01-0001601.tkl|quote={{lang|el|\u0391\u03b9 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0392\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03b3\u03ac\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd \u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03b9 \u03ad\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03b5\u03be\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u03bf\u03c7\u03b7\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf \u03b5\u03c0\u03af \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392. \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391. \u03a4\u03b6. \u039f\u03b4\u03bf\u03cd, \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bc\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b9\u03c3\u03c7\u03c5\u03c1\u03ac\u03c2 \u03b4\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bc\u03b5\u03c9\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5\u03ba\u03b9\u03bd\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf \u03b5\u03ba \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b4\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ac\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03ac\u03bd \u03cc\u03c7\u03b8\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c3\u03bf\u03b2\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03af \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c5\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac\u03b6\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af \u03c4\u03bf \u03c5\u03c8. 546, \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af \u03c4\u03b1 3 \u03c7\u03bb\u03bc. \u0392. \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391. \u03a4\u03b6.. \u03ae\u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b5\u03af\u03c7\u03b5 \u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03ae.}}}}</ref> On the following day, the counterattacking Bulgarians attempted to encircle the outnumbered Greeks in a [[Battle of Cannae|Cannae]]-type battle by applying pressure on their flanks.<ref name=\"Hall\"/> Nevertheless, the Greeks launched counter-attacks at [[Mehomia]] and to the west of [[Kresna Gorge|Kresna]] and by July 30 the Bulgarian attacks had subsided somewhat. On the eastern flank, the Greek army launched an counterattack towards Mehomia through the Predela pass. The offensive was stopped by the Bulgarian army on the eastern side of the pass and fighting ground to a stalemate. On the western flank, an offensive was launched against Charevo Selo with the objection of reaching the Serbian lines. This failed and the Bulgarian army continued advancing, especially in the south, where by the 29th of July the Bulgarian forces had cut the Greek line of retreat through Berovo and Strumitsa, leaving the Greek army with only one route of retreat.<ref>History of the Bulgarians: The Military history of the Bulgarians from Ancient times until present day, Georgi Bakalov, 2007,[https://books.google.com/books?id=HDQn3tJkyUcC&pg=PA414 p.452]</ref><ref name=\"Price\">{{cite book| last =Price  | first =Crawfurd| title =The Balkan cockpit| publisher =T. Werner Laurie LTD| year =1914}}</ref><ref>History of the Macedonian-Adrianopolitan Volunteer Corps, Petar Darvingov, 1925, book II, p.712-714 (in Bulgarian)</ref>{{Verify source|date=January 2012}} However, after a three days fighting at the sectors of Pehchevo and Mahomia, the Greek forces retained their positions.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=261|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n4-RAAAAIAAJ|edition=1.udg.}}</ref> On July 30, the Greek headquarters planned to launch a new attack in order to advance towards the sector of Gorna Dzhumaya.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=262|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ci9pAAAAMAAJ|edition=1.udg.}}</ref> On that day hostilities continued with the Bulgarian forces deployed on strategic positions north and northeast of the town.<ref>{{cite book|title=Great Military and Naval Encyclopedia|year=1929|publisher=\u0388\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u039d\u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0395\u03b3\u03ba\u03c5\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|location=Athens|pages=301|accessdate=2 July 2012|language=Greek|volume=6|url=http://anemi.lib.uoc.gr/metadata/e/3/e/metadata-01-0001601.tkl|quote={{lang|el|17 \u0399\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd\u03af\u03bf\u03c5: \u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bd\u03cd\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \u0393\u03b5\u03bd. \u03a3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4. \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd. \u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd... \u03b2\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03b5\u03af\u03c3\u03b1 \u03b5\u03ba \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0392. \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b4\u03ac\u03c3\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2, \u03b5\u03c0\u03ad\u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b5\u03c8\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b7 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03ce\u03c3\u03b1\u03c3\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2.}}}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Battle of Kresna Map.png|thumb|260px|Demarcation line and disposition of the Greek forces, following the armistice.]]\nMeanwhile,  King Constantine, who had neglected the initial Bulgarian requests for truce and wanted to capture Sofia, Bulgaria's capital, now informed Venizelos, that his army was \"''physically and morally exhausted''\" and urged him to seek cessation of hostilities<ref name=\"Hall\"/> through Romanian mediation. The resulted general armistice, signed on {{OldStyleDate|July, 31|1913|July, 18}} in [[Bucharest]], ended one of the bloodiest battles of the Second Balkan War.\n\n==Legacy==\nArmistice left both parties claiming victory. From the Greek point of view, after 11 days of attack the Bulgarians had clearly failed to turn the Greek army's flanks, and consequently they consider the battle a defensive victory.<ref name=\"Price\"/> To the Bulgarians, the battle was a victory since their attack successfully stopped the Greek Army's advance towards Sofia and thus induced the Greeks to accept the proposed armistice. This view is supported by the opinion held by some historians that although the battle was ended inconclusively by the armistice, by the end of the war the Greek army was threatened by encirclement and annihilation.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite book| last =Hall  | first =Richard   | title =The Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913: Prelude to the First World War| publisher =Routledge| year =2000 | isbn =0-415-22946-4  | pages =121\u2013122 }}</ref> The Greek side on the other claims that during the prolonged battle, the Bulgarians had progressively involved all available forces, and lacked the additional manpower to complete the encirclement of the Greek forces.\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Price W. H. Crawfurd. [https://books.google.com/books?id=lS2MZbW3P18C&dq= ''The Balkan Cockpit \u2013 The Political and Military Story of the Balkan Wars in Macedonia'']. Read Books, 2008. {{ISBN|978-1-4437-7404-8}}.\n*{{cite book|last=Hall|first=Richard C.|title=The Balkan wars 1912 \u2013 1913 : prelude to the First World War|year=2000|publisher=Routledge|location=London [u.a.]|isbn=9780415229463|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZSllgZ-1D4YC&dq=isbn:0415229464|edition=Repr.}}\n\n{{Commons category|Battle of Kresna Gorge}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kresna Gorge}}\n[[Category:Battles of the Second Balkan War]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1913]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Greece]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:July 1913 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Kresna Gorge \n|partof=[[Second Balkan War]]   \n|image=  Greek advance Kresna 1913.jpg\n|image_size=  240px\n|caption=Greek units advancing in Kresna Gorge\n|date={{OldStyleDate|July, 21-31|1913|July, 8-18}}\n|place=[[Kresna Gorge]], [[Bulgaria]]  \n|result=Stalemate brought about by truce\n|combatant1=[[File:Flag of Bulgaria.svg|border|22px]] [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]]  \n|combatant2=[[File:Flag of Greece (1828-1978).svg|22px]] [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]]   \n|commander1=Gen. [[Mihail Savov]] <br> Gen. [[Nikola Ivanov]]\n|commander2=King [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine I]] \n|strength1=110 battalions{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n|strength2=80 battalions{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=10,000<ref>Cassavetti, D. J. ''Hellas and the Balkan wars.'' T. Fisher Unwin, London 1914. \u0440. 334</ref>\n}}   \n{{Campaignbox Second Balkan War}}\nThe '''Battle of Kresna Gorge''' was fought in 1913 between the [[Greeks]] and the [[Bulgarians]] during the [[Second Balkan War]]. It marked the last phase of the Greek advance into Bulgarian territory before the ceasefire and the following peace treaty.\n\n==Background==\nAfter the Serbian front became static, and seeing that the Bulgarian Army in his front had already suffered defeat, [[Constantine I of Greece|King Constantine]] ordered the Greek Army to march further into Bulgarian territory and take the capital city of [[Sofia]]. \n[[Constantine I of Greece|King Constantine]] wanted a decisive victory on this war despite the objections of Prime Minister [[Eleftherios Venizelos]] who realized that the Serbs, having won their territorial objectives, were now trying to move the weight of the rest of the war to the Greeks by staying passive. The battle was continued for eleven days, between July 8\u201318, over a front of 20&nbsp;km, in a maze of forests and mountains.\n\n==Conflict==\n\n===Greek advance and breaking through the Kresna pass ===\nAfter the victorious [[Battle of Doiran (1913)|Battle of Doiran]] the Greek forces continued their penetration north. On July 18, the [[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st Greek Division]], managed to drive back the Bulgarian rear guard and captured an important foothold at the southern end of the Kresna pass.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hellenic Army General Staff, Army History Directorate. [Ed. committee: Dimitrios Gedeon|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912-1913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=9789607897077|pages=254|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ci9pAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22and+captured+important+footholds+at+the+southern+exit%22&q=%22On+8+July%2C+after+a+tough+struggle%2C+the+division+drove+back+a+strong+Bulgarian+rear+guard+in+the+area+of+the+village+of+Yenikoy%2C+and+captured+important+footholds+at+the+southern+exit+of+the+Kresna+defile.%22#search_anchor|edition=1.udg.}}</ref>\n\nIn the pass, the Greeks were ambushed by the Bulgarian 2nd and 4th Armies which was newly arrived from the Serbian front and had taken up defensive positions there. However, after bitter fighting the Greek side managed to break through the Kresna pass. The Greek advance continued and on July 25, the village of Krupnik, north of the pass, was captured, forcing the Bulgarian troops to withdraw to [[Simitli]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912-1913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=257|url=https://books.google.com/?id=n4-RAAAAIAAJ&dq=%22was+confronted%2C+the+Bulgarian+attack+was+succesfully+repelled%3B+after+a+tough%2C+three-day+struggle+the+Greek+forces+were+once+again+masters+of+the+battlefield.%22&q=%22krupnik+during+the+night+of+11-12+July%22#search_anchor|edition=1.udg.}}</ref> Simitli was also captured on July 26,<ref>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912-1913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=259|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ci9pAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Finally%20they%20forced%20the%20Bulgarians%20to%20abandon%20Summit%201378%20on%20the%20night%22%20Dzhumaya|edition=1.udg.}}</ref> while at the night of July 27\u201328 the Bulgarian forces were pushed north to Gorna Dzhumaya ([[Blagoevgrad]]), 76&nbsp;km south of [[Sofia]].<ref name=Gedeon260>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912-1913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=260|url=https://books.google.com/?id=n4-RAAAAIAAJ&dq=%22Finally+they+forced+the+Bulgarians+to+abandon+Summit+1378+on+the+night%22+Dzhumaya&q=%22Finally+they+forced+the+Bulgarians+to+abandon+Summit+1378+on+the+night+of+14-15+July+and+withdraw+towards+Dzhumaya.+On+the+same+day+in+western+Thrace%2C+Division+VIII%2C+unopposed%2C+liberated+the+city+of+Komotene.+%22#search_anchor|edition=1.udg.}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the Greek forces continued their march inland into western Thrace and on July 26, entered [[Xanthi]] and the next day entered [[Komotini]], without facing opposition.<ref name=Gedeon260/>\n\n===Bulgarian counterattack and armistice===\n[[File:Map Battle Simitli 1079 1378.jpeg|thumbnail|left|Advance of the Greek forces after breaking through the Kresna Gorge (July, 25-30)]]\nThe Greek army was stopped in front of Gorna Dzhumaya by significant Bulgarian resistance.<ref>History of the Bulgarians: The Military history of the Bulgarians from Ancient times until present day, Georgi Bakalov, 2007, [https://books.google.com/books?id=HDQn3tJkyUcC&pg=PA450&dq=%22%D0%B3%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B0+%D0%B4%D0%B6%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%B0%D1%8F%22+1913+%D0%BA%D1%80%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=QIfKT9LvHuin4gSxzekp&redir_esc=y#v=snippet&q=%22%D1%81%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B8%D0%BE%D0%B7%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%B0%20%D1%81%D1%8A%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%BE%D1%82%D0%B8%D0%B2%D0%B0%2C%20%D0%BA%D0%BE%D1%8F%D1%82%D0%BE%20%D1%87%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B5%20%D0%BD%D0%B0%202-%D1%80%D0%B0%20%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%BC%D0%B8%D1%8F%20%D0%BE%D0%BA%D0%B0%D0%B7%D0%B2%D0%B0%D1%82%20%D0%BF%D0%BE%20%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%81%D0%BE%D1%87%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B5%20%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B4%20%D0%93%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B0%20%D0%94%D0%B6%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%B0%D1%8F%22&f=false p.450], {{in lang|bg}}</ref><ref>Historical overview, Volume 38, Issues 4-6, 1982, [https://books.google.com/books?ei=QIfKT9LvHuin4gSxzekp&id=eBNpAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22%D0%B3%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B0+%D0%B4%D0%B6%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%B0%D1%8F%22+1913+%D0%BA%D1%80%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B0&q=%22%D0%B3%D1%80%D1%8A%D1%86%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B5+%D0%B4%D0%B8%D0%B2%D0%B8%D0%B7%D0%B8%D0%B8%2C+%D1%87%D0%B8%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%BE+%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B4%D0%BD%D0%B8+%D1%87%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B8+%D0%B4%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%85%D0%B0+%D1%8E%D0%B6%D0%BD%D0%BE+%D0%BE%D1%82+%D0%93%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B0+%D0%B4%D0%B6%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%B0%D1%8F%22#search_anchor p.112] {{in lang|bg}}</ref> In July 28, the Greek forces resumed the attack and captured a line stretching from Cherovo to Hill 1378, southeast of Gorna Dzhumaya.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hellenic Army General Staff, Army History Directorate. [Ed. committee: Dimitrios Gedeon|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912-1913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=9789607897077|pages=261|url=https://books.google.com/?id=n4-RAAAAIAAJ&dq=%22hasan+pasha+height%2C+and+with%22&q=%22On+the+morning+of+15+July%2C+while+the+Greek+forces+were+resuming+the+attack+with+Divisions+II+and+IV+against+the+Hasan+Pasha+height%2C+and+with+Divisions+I%2C+V%2C+VI+and+VII+were+capturing+the+line+from+Cherov%27o+to+Hill+1378%2C+%22#search_anchor|edition=1.udg.}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on the evening of July 28, under heavy pressure, the Bulgarian army was forced to abandon the town, while it set fire to a quarter of it during the retreat.<ref>Price, Crawfurd (1914). The Balkan cockpit. T. Werner Laurie LTD, p. 336</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Great Military and Naval Encyclopedia|year=1929|publisher=\u0388\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u039d\u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0395\u03b3\u03ba\u03c5\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|location=Athens|pages=300|accessdate=2 July 2012|language=Greek|volume=6|url=http://anemi.lib.uoc.gr/metadata/e/3/e/metadata-01-0001601.tkl|quote={{lang|el|\u0391\u03b9 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0392\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03b3\u03ac\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd \u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03b9 \u03ad\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03b5\u03be\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u03bf\u03c7\u03b7\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf \u03b5\u03c0\u03af \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392. \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391. \u03a4\u03b6. \u039f\u03b4\u03bf\u03cd, \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bc\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b9\u03c3\u03c7\u03c5\u03c1\u03ac\u03c2 \u03b4\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bc\u03b5\u03c9\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5\u03ba\u03b9\u03bd\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf \u03b5\u03ba \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b4\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ac\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03ac\u03bd \u03cc\u03c7\u03b8\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c3\u03bf\u03b2\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03af \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c5\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac\u03b6\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af \u03c4\u03bf \u03c5\u03c8. 546, \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af \u03c4\u03b1 3 \u03c7\u03bb\u03bc. \u0392. \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391. \u03a4\u03b6.. \u03ae\u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b5\u03af\u03c7\u03b5 \u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03ae.}}}}</ref> On the following day, the counterattacking Bulgarians attempted to encircle the outnumbered Greeks in a [[Battle of Cannae|Cannae]]-type battle by applying pressure on their flanks.<ref name=\"Hall\"/> Nevertheless, the Greeks launched counter-attacks at [[Mehomia]] and to the west of [[Kresna Gorge|Kresna]] and by July 30 the Bulgarian attacks had subsided somewhat. On the eastern flank, the Greek army launched an counterattack towards Mehomia through the Predela pass. The offensive was stopped by the Bulgarian army on the eastern side of the pass and fighting ground to a stalemate. On the western flank, an offensive was launched against Charevo Selo with the objection of reaching the Serbian lines. This failed and the Bulgarian army continued advancing, especially in the south, where by the 29th of July the Bulgarian forces had cut the Greek line of retreat through Berovo and Strumitsa, leaving the Greek army with only one route of retreat.<ref>History of the Bulgarians: The Military history of the Bulgarians from Ancient times until present day, Georgi Bakalov, 2007,[https://books.google.com/books?id=HDQn3tJkyUcC&pg=PA414&dq=%D0%91%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%BA%D0%B0%D0%BD%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%B0+%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%B9%D0%BD%D0%B0+1912-1913+%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%B4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3AfyT8i3AeSB4gTHvsnBDQ&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22%D0%B1%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE-%D1%81%D1%82%D1%80%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%B8%D1%86%D0%B0%22&f=false p.452]</ref><ref name=\"Price\">{{cite book| last =Price  | first =Crawfurd| title =The Balkan cockpit| publisher =T. Werner Laurie LTD| year =1914}}</ref><ref>History of the Macedonian-Adrianopolitan Volunteer Corps, Petar Darvingov, 1925, book II, p.712-714 (in Bulgarian)</ref>{{Verify source|date=January 2012}} However, after a three days fighting at the sectors of Pehchevo and Mahomia, the Greek forces retained their positions.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912-1913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=261|url=https://books.google.com/?id=n4-RAAAAIAAJ&dq=%22was+confronted%2C+the+Bulgarian+attack+was+succesfully+repelled%3B+after+a+tough%2C+three-day+struggle+the+Greek+forces+were+once+again+masters+of+the+battlefield.%22&q=%22Thanks%2C+however%2C+to+the+courage+and+decisiveness+with+which+it+was+confronted%2C+the+Bulgarian+attack+was+successfully+repelled%3B+after+a+tough%2C+three-day+struggle+the+Greek+forces+were+once+again+masters+of+the+battlefield.%22#search_anchor|edition=1.udg.}}</ref> On July 30, the Greek headquarters planned to launch a new attack in order to advance towards the sector of Gorna Dzhumaya.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gedeon|first=Dimitrios|title=A concise history of the Balkan Wars, 1912-1913|year=1998|publisher=Hellenic Army General Staff|location=Athens|isbn=978-960-7897-07-7|pages=262|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ci9pAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22division+VI+would+assemple+south+of+Moshtantsa%2C+as+a+reserve%22&q=%22Division+VI+would+assemble+south+of+Moshtantsa%2C+as+a+reserve+force%22#search_anchor|edition=1.udg.}}</ref> On that day hostilities continued with the Bulgarian forces deployed on strategic positions north and northeast of the town.<ref>{{cite book|title=Great Military and Naval Encyclopedia|year=1929|publisher=\u0388\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u039d\u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0395\u03b3\u03ba\u03c5\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|location=Athens|pages=301|accessdate=2 July 2012|language=Greek|volume=6|url=http://anemi.lib.uoc.gr/metadata/e/3/e/metadata-01-0001601.tkl|quote={{lang|el|17 \u0399\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd\u03af\u03bf\u03c5: \u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bd\u03cd\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \u0393\u03b5\u03bd. \u03a3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4. \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd. \u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd... \u03b2\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03b5\u03af\u03c3\u03b1 \u03b5\u03ba \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0392. \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b4\u03ac\u03c3\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2, \u03b5\u03c0\u03ad\u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b5\u03c8\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b7 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03ce\u03c3\u03b1\u03c3\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2.}}}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Battle of Kresna Map.png|thumb|260px|Demarcation line and disposition of the Greek forces, following the armistice.]]\nMeanwhile,  King Constantine, who had neglected the initial Bulgarian requests for truce and wanted to capture Sofia, Bulgaria's capital, now informed Venizelos, that his army was \"''physically and morally exhausted''\" and urged him to seek cessation of hostilities<ref name=\"Hall\"/> through Romanian mediation. The resulted general armistice, signed on {{OldStyleDate|July, 31|1913|July, 18}} in [[Bucharest]], ended one of the bloodiest battles of the Second Balkan War.\n\n==Legacy==\nArmistice left both parties claiming victory. From the Greek point of view, after 11 days of attack the Bulgarians had clearly failed to turn the Greek army's flanks, and consequently they consider the battle a defensive victory.<ref name=\"Price\"/> To the Bulgarians, the battle was a victory since their attack successfully stopped the Greek Army's advance towards Sofia and thus induced the Greeks to accept the proposed armistice. This view is supported by the opinion held by some historians that although the battle was ended inconclusively by the armistice, by the end of the war the Greek army was threatened by encirclement and annihilation.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite book| last =Hall  | first =Richard   | title =The Balkan Wars, 1912-1913: Prelude to the First World War| publisher =Routledge| year =2000 | isbn =0-415-22946-4  | pages =121\u2013122 }}</ref> The Greek side on the other claims that during the prolonged battle, the Bulgarians had progressively involved all available forces, and lacked the additional manpower to complete the encirclement of the Greek forces.\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Price W. H. Crawfurd. [https://books.google.com/books?id=lS2MZbW3P18C&dq= ''The Balkan Cockpit - The Political and Military Story of the Balkan Wars in Macedonia'']. Read Books, 2008. {{ISBN|978-1-4437-7404-8}}.\n*{{cite book|last=Hall|first=Richard C.|title=The Balkan wars 1912 - 1913 : prelude to the First World War|year=2000|publisher=Routledge|location=London [u.a.]|isbn=9780415229463|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZSllgZ-1D4YC&dq=isbn:0415229464|edition=Repr.}}\n\n{{Commons category|Battle of Kresna Gorge}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kresna Gorge}}\n[[Category:Battles of the Second Balkan War]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1913]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Greece]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:July 1913 events]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:DASH, link maintenance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Kresna_Gorge"}
{"title_page": "The rich get richer and the poor get poorer", "text_new": "{{About|the catchphrase|the theoretical process|wealth concentration|and|capital accumulation|a full discussion of the social, economic, and political phenomena to which the phrase refers|economic inequality}}\n{{redirect|Rich get richer|the generative model|Scale-free network#Generative models}}\n\n\"'''The rich get richer and the poor get poorer'''\" is an [[aphorism]] due to [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]. In ''[[A Defence of Poetry]]'' (1821, not published until 1840) Shelley remarked that [[Utilitarianism|the promoters of utility]] had exemplified the saying, \"To him that hath, more shall be given; and from him that hath not, the little that he hath shall be taken away.\" The rich have become richer, and the poor have become poorer; and the vessel of the State is driven [[Between Scylla and Charybdis|between the Scylla and Charybdis]] of anarchy and [[despotism]].<ref>{{cite book|title=A Defence of Poetry (from the Harvard Classics: English Essays: Sidney to Macaulay|last=Shelley|first=Percy Bysshe|publisher=Bartleby.com|year=1909\u201314}}</ref>\n\n\"To him that hath\" ''etc''. is a reference to Matthew 25:29 (the [[Parable of the talents or minas|parable of the talents]], see also [[Matthew effect]]). The aphorism is commonly evoked, with variations in wording, as a synopsis of the effect of [[free market]] [[capitalism]] producing [[Economic inequality|inequality]].\n\n==Predecessors==\n[[Andrew Jackson]], the seventh President of the U.S. (1829\u20131837), in his 1832 [[Second Bank of the United States|bank veto]], said that\n: when the laws undertake... to make the rich richer and the potent more powerful, the humble members of society... have a right to complain of the injustice to their Government.<ref>{{cite book|title=Andrew Jackson V. Henry Clay: Democracy and Development in Antebellum America|last=Watson|first=Harry L.|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=1998|isbn=0-312-17772-0}} [https://www.amazon.com/gp/reader/0312177720/?keywords=%22rich+richer%22&v=search-inside]</ref><ref>{{gutenberg|no=10858 |name=A Compilation of the Messages and Papers of the Presidents,  Vol. 2, Part 3, Andrew Jackson, 1st term}}</ref>\n\nThe phrase also resembles two [[Bible]] verses from the [[Gospel of Matthew]]:\n: For whosoever hath, to him shall be given, and he shall have more abundance: but whosoever hath not, from him shall be taken away even that he hath.<ref>{{Bibleverse|Matthew|13:12|KJV}}</ref>\n: For unto every one that hath shall be given, and he shall have abundance: but from him that hath not shall be taken away even that which he hath.<ref>{{Bibleverse|Matthew|25:29|KJV}}</ref>\n\n==\"Ain't We Got Fun\"==\nThe phrase was popularized in 1921 in the wildly successful song \"[[Ain't We Got Fun]]?\", and the phrase is sometimes attributed to the song's lyricists, [[Gus Kahn]] and [[Raymond B. Egan]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://everything2.net/index.pl?node_id=1101156 |title = Ain't We Got Fun |accessdate = 2006-08-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.geocities.com/dferg5493/aintwegotfun.htm |title = Ain't We Got Fun |publisher = Don Ferguson |accessdate = 2006-08-11 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20041210204617/http://www.geocities.com/dferg5493/aintwegotfun.htm |archivedate = 2004-12-10 }}</ref>\nThe line is sometimes mistakenly attributed to [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]]. It appears in ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', as \n: the rich get richer and the poor get&mdash;children!\nThe character Gatsby orders the character Klipspringer, sitting at the piano, \"Don't talk so much, old sport... Play!\" and Klipspringer breaks into the Whiting, Kahn and Egan song.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Great Gatsby|last=Fitzgerald|first=F. Scott|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1998|isbn=0-19-283269-7|origyear=1921}} [https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN0192832697&id=ZMQv026FgT8C&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&sig=TXJ-bqB-iGfrDrPn5AaxBl7Z7fc p. 76]; also at Project Gutenberg of Australia [http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks02/0200041.txt]</ref>\n\n==In economics==\n[[Thomas Piketty]]'s book ''[[Capital in the Twenty-First Century]]'' (2014) presents a body of empirical data spanning several hundred years that supports his central thesis that the owners of capital accumulate wealth more quickly than those who provide labour, a phenomenon widely described with the term \"the rich-get-richer\".<ref>https://newrepublic.com/article/117429/capital-twenty-first-century-thomas-piketty-reviewed</ref>\n\n== In modern politics ==\nIn the United States, the phrase has been used frequently to describe socioeconomic trends under the [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[George H. W. Bush]] presidencies,<ref>[[James K. Galbraith]]. \"[http://archive.salon.com/opinion/feature/2004/06/08/reaganomics/index_np.html The rich got richer] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929143539/http://archive.salon.com/opinion/feature/2004/06/08/reaganomics/index_np.html |date=2007-09-29 }}.\" ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', June 8, 2004</ref><ref>Edward N. Wolf. \"[http://www.epinet.org/content.cfm/paycheck_wages_summary_wages The rich get increasingly richer: Latest data on household wealth during the 1980s] {{Webarchive|url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20041023043625/http://www.epinet.org/content.cfm/paycheck_wages_summary_wages |date=2004-10-23 }}.\" [[Economic Policy Institute]] Briefing Paper #36. 1993.</ref><ref>[[Alan Reynolds (economist)|Alan Reynolds]]. \"[http://www.nationalreview.com/reagan/reynolds200406101357.asp Upstarts and Downstarts] (The Real Reagan Record).\" ''National Review'', August 31, 1992.</ref> and in the [[United Kingdom]] to refer to the [[Premiership of Margaret Thatcher|Thatcher era]].<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Nunns |first1 = Alex |title = Dispelling the Thatcher myths |url = http://www.redpepper.org.uk/dispelling-the-thatcher-myths/ |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = Red Pepper |date = April 2013 |quote = It's said that Thatcher made the British people richer. She didn't. ... The rich got richer; the poor got poorer. }}</ref> Thatcher famously retorted to a question posed by the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Lib Dem]] MP [[Simon Hughes]] about [[Economic inequality|wealth inequality]] in the United Kingdom by saying \"he would rather that the poor were poorer, provided that the rich were less rich. ... What a policy. Yes, he would rather have the poor poorer, provided that the rich were less rich. That is the Liberal policy.\"<ref>{{cite news |title = HC S: [Confidence in Her Majesty's Government] |url = http://www.margaretthatcher.org/document/108256 |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = House of Commons Speech |issue = 22 November 1990 |publisher = [[Hansard]]  HC [181/445-53] |via = Margaret Thatcher Foundation |date = 22 November 1990 |quote = People on all levels of income are better off than they were in 1979. The hon. Gentleman is saying that he would rather that the poor were poorer, provided that the rich were less rich. That way one will never create the wealth for better social services, as we have. What a policy. Yes, he would rather have the poor poorer, provided that the rich were less rich. That is the Liberal policy. }}</ref> It has also been used in the UK to refer to [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|the 2010\u20132015 coalition]] and [[Second Cameron ministry|2015\u20132016]] governments led by [[David Cameron]].<ref>Coalition:\n\n*{{cite news |title = Tories Make the Rich Richer and the Poor Poorer |url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/kamran-hussain/david-cameron-austerity_b_4310611.html |work = The Huffington Post UK |language = en-GB }}\n*{{cite news |last1 = Waugh |first1 = Rob |title = Rich have become richer thanks to 'austerity' politics - but poor lose out |url = http://metro.co.uk/2014/11/16/rich-have-become-richer-thanks-to-austerity-politics-but-poor-lose-out-4950177/ |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = Metro |date = 16 November 2014 }}\n2015\u2013present:\n\n*{{cite news |title = Labour: soaring levels of homelessness under Cameron mean more children facing Christmas on streets |url = http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/14160723.Labour__soaring_levels_of_homelessness_under_Cameron_mean_more_children_facing_Christmas_on_streets/ |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = Herald Scotland }}\n*{{cite news |title = Cameron tries to soothe MPs ahead of challenging year for party management |url = http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/01/cameron-tries-to-soothe-mps-ahead-of-difficult-year-for-party-management/ |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = Coffee House |date = 2 January 2016 |language = en-US }}</ref>\n\n==Other uses==\nIn [[statistics]], the phrase \"the rich get richer\" is often used as an informal description of the behavior of [[Chinese restaurant process]]es and other [[preferential attachment]] processes, where the probability of the next outcome in a series taking on a particular value is proportional to the number of outcomes already having that particular value.  This is useful for modeling many real-world processes that are akin to \"popularity contests\", where the popularity of a particular choice causes new participants to adopt the same choice (which can lead to the outsized influence of the first few participants).\n\n===Markets with social influence===\nProduct recommendations and information about past purchases have been shown to influence consumers choices significantly whether it is for music, movie, book, technological, and other type of products. Social influence often induces a rich-get-richer phenomenon ([[Matthew effect]]) where popular products tend to become even more popular.<ref name=\"altszyler2017\">{{cite journal | url= http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0180040 | title= Transient dynamics in trial-offer markets with social influence: Trade-offs between appeal and quality. |author1= Altszyler, E |author2=Berbeglia, F.| author3= Berbeglia, G. |author4=Van Hentenryck, P. | journal=  PLoS ONE | year=2017 |volume=12|issue=7 | doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0180040 | page=e0180040|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1280040A | pmc=5528888 | pmid=28746334}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Economic inequality}}\n* [[Capital accumulation]]\t\n* [[Internal contradictions of capital accumulation]]\n* [[Matthew effect]]\n* [[Preferential attachment]]\n* [[Socialism for the rich and capitalism for the poor]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Hayes |first1 = Brian |title = Follow the Money |journal = American Scientist |volume = 90 |issue = 5 |pages = 400 |year = 2002 |doi = 10.1511/2002.5.400 }} &mdash; Hayes analyzes several computer models of market economies, applying statistical mechanics to questions in economic theory in the same way that it is applied in [[computational fluid dynamics]], concluding that \"If some mechanism like that of the yard-sale model is truly at work, then markets might very well be free and fair, and the playing field perfectly level, and yet the outcome would almost surely be that the rich get richer and the poor get poorer.\"\n* {{cite book |author = Rieman, J. |year = 1979 |title = The Rich Get Rich and The Poor Get Poorer |publisher = Wiley |location = New York }}\n* {{cite book |title = The Screwing of the Average Man &mdash; How The Rich Get Richer and You Get Poorer |author = David Hapgood |publisher = Bantom Books |year = 1974 |isbn = 0-553-12913-9 |url-access = registration |url = https://archive.org/details/screwingofavera00bant }}\n* {{cite book |title = Why the rich get richer and the poor get poorer |author = Rolf R Mantel |publisher = Victoria, prov. de Buenos Aires |location = Universidad de San Andr\u00e9s |year = 1995 |id = OCLC 44260846 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Ispolatov |first1 = S. |last2 = Krapivsky |first2 = P.L. |last3 = Redner |first3 = S. |title = Wealth distributions in asset exchange models |journal = The European Physical Journal B |volume = 2 |issue = 2 |pages = 267\u201376 |year = 1998 |doi = 10.1007/s100510050249 |arxiv = 1006.4595 |bibcode = 1998EPJB....2..267I }} &mdash; Ispolatov, Krapivsky, and Redner analyze the wealth distributions that occur under a variety of exchange rules in a system of economically interacting people.\n* {{cite journal |pages = 301\u20139 |issue = 1 |volume = 45 |last1 = Chung |year = 1990 |doi = 10.2307/2328824 |journal = The Journal of Finance |first1 = Kee H. |last2 = Cox |first2 = Raymond A. K. |title = Patterns of Productivity in the Finance Literature: A Study of the Bibliometric Distributions |jstor = 2328824 }} &mdash; Chung and Cox analyze a bibliometric regularity in finance literature, relating [[Lotka's law|Lotka's law of scientific productivity]] to the maxim that \"the rich get richer and the poor get poorer\", and equating it to the maxim that \"success breeds success\".\n\n{{Extreme wealth}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rich Get Richer And The Poor Get Poorer}}\n[[Category:Wealth concentration]]\n[[Category:Economic inequality]]\n[[Category:American political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Adages]]\n[[Category:Economics catchphrases]]\n[[Category:British political phrases]]\n[[Category:Quotations from literature]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in the 19th century]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the catchphrase|the theoretical process|wealth concentration|and|capital accumulation|a full discussion of the social, economic, and political phenomena to which the phrase refers|economic inequality}}\n{{redirect|Rich get richer|the generative model|Scale-free network#Generative models}}\n\n\"'''The rich get richer and the poor get poorer'''\" is an [[aphorism]] due to [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]. In ''[[A Defence of Poetry]]'' (1821, not published until 1840) Shelley remarked that [[Utilitarianism|the promoters of utility]] had\n\n: exemplified the saying, \"To him that hath, more shall be given; and from him that hath not, the little that he hath shall be taken away.\" The rich have become richer, and the poor have become poorer; and the vessel of the State is driven [[Between Scylla and Charybdis|between the Scylla and Charybdis]] of anarchy and [[despotism]].<ref>{{cite book|title=A Defence of Poetry (from the Harvard Classics: English Essays: Sidney to Macaulay|last=Shelley|first=Percy Bysshe|publisher=Bartleby.com|year=1909\u201314}}</ref>\n\n\"To him that hath\" ''etc''. is a reference to Matthew 25:29 (the [[Parable of the talents or minas|parable of the talents]], see also [[Matthew effect]]). The aphorism is commonly evoked, with variations in wording, as a synopsis of the effect of [[free market]] [[capitalism]] producing [[Economic inequality|inequality]].\n\n==Predecessors==\n[[Andrew Jackson]], the seventh President of the U.S. (1829\u20131837), in his 1832 [[Second Bank of the United States|bank veto]], said that\n: when the laws undertake... to make the rich richer and the potent more powerful, the humble members of society... have a right to complain of the injustice to their Government.<ref>{{cite book|title=Andrew Jackson V. Henry Clay: Democracy and Development in Antebellum America|last=Watson|first=Harry L.|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=1998|isbn=0-312-17772-0}} [https://www.amazon.com/gp/reader/0312177720/?keywords=%22rich+richer%22&v=search-inside]</ref><ref>{{gutenberg|no=10858 |name=A Compilation of the Messages and Papers of the Presidents,  Vol. 2, Part 3, Andrew Jackson, 1st term}}</ref>\n\nThe phrase also resembles two [[Bible]] verses from the [[Gospel of Matthew]]:\n: For whosoever hath, to him shall be given, and he shall have more abundance: but whosoever hath not, from him shall be taken away even that he hath.<ref>{{Bibleverse|Matthew|13:12|KJV}}</ref>\n: For unto every one that hath shall be given, and he shall have abundance: but from him that hath not shall be taken away even that which he hath.<ref>{{Bibleverse|Matthew|25:29|KJV}}</ref>\n\n==\"Ain't We Got Fun\"==\nThe phrase was popularized in 1921 in the wildly successful song \"[[Ain't We Got Fun]]?\", and the phrase is sometimes attributed to the song's lyricists, [[Gus Kahn]] and [[Raymond B. Egan]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://everything2.net/index.pl?node_id=1101156 |title = Ain't We Got Fun |accessdate = 2006-08-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.geocities.com/dferg5493/aintwegotfun.htm |title = Ain't We Got Fun |publisher = Don Ferguson |accessdate = 2006-08-11 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20041210204617/http://www.geocities.com/dferg5493/aintwegotfun.htm |archivedate = 2004-12-10 }}</ref>\nThe line is sometimes mistakenly attributed to [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]]. It appears in ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', as \n: the rich get richer and the poor get&mdash;children!\nThe character Gatsby orders the character Klipspringer, sitting at the piano, \"Don't talk so much, old sport... Play!\" and Klipspringer breaks into the Whiting, Kahn and Egan song.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Great Gatsby|last=Fitzgerald|first=F. Scott|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1998|isbn=0-19-283269-7|origyear=1921}} [https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN0192832697&id=ZMQv026FgT8C&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&sig=TXJ-bqB-iGfrDrPn5AaxBl7Z7fc p. 76]; also at Project Gutenberg of Australia [http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks02/0200041.txt]</ref>\n\n==In economics==\n[[Thomas Piketty]]'s book ''[[Capital in the Twenty-First Century]]'' (2014) presents a body of empirical data spanning several hundred years that supports his central thesis that the owners of capital accumulate wealth more quickly than those who provide labour, a phenomenon widely described with the term \"the rich-get-richer\".<ref>https://newrepublic.com/article/117429/capital-twenty-first-century-thomas-piketty-reviewed</ref>\n\n== In modern politics ==\nIn the United States, the phrase has been used frequently to describe socioeconomic trends under the [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[George H. W. Bush]] presidencies,<ref>[[James K. Galbraith]]. \"[http://archive.salon.com/opinion/feature/2004/06/08/reaganomics/index_np.html The rich got richer] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929143539/http://archive.salon.com/opinion/feature/2004/06/08/reaganomics/index_np.html |date=2007-09-29 }}.\" ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', June 8, 2004</ref><ref>Edward N. Wolf. \"[http://www.epinet.org/content.cfm/paycheck_wages_summary_wages The rich get increasingly richer: Latest data on household wealth during the 1980s] {{Webarchive|url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20041023043625/http://www.epinet.org/content.cfm/paycheck_wages_summary_wages |date=2004-10-23 }}.\" [[Economic Policy Institute]] Briefing Paper #36. 1993.</ref><ref>[[Alan Reynolds (economist)|Alan Reynolds]]. \"[http://www.nationalreview.com/reagan/reynolds200406101357.asp Upstarts and Downstarts] (The Real Reagan Record).\" ''National Review'', August 31, 1992.</ref> and in the [[United Kingdom]] to refer to the [[Premiership of Margaret Thatcher|Thatcher era]].<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Nunns |first1 = Alex |title = Dispelling the Thatcher myths |url = http://www.redpepper.org.uk/dispelling-the-thatcher-myths/ |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = Red Pepper |date = April 2013 |quote = It's said that Thatcher made the British people richer. She didn't. ... The rich got richer; the poor got poorer. }}</ref> Thatcher famously retorted to a question posed by the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Lib Dem]] MP [[Simon Hughes]] about [[Economic inequality|wealth inequality]] in the United Kingdom by saying \"he would rather that the poor were poorer, provided that the rich were less rich. ... What a policy. Yes, he would rather have the poor poorer, provided that the rich were less rich. That is the Liberal policy.\"<ref>{{cite news |title = HC S: [Confidence in Her Majesty's Government] |url = http://www.margaretthatcher.org/document/108256 |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = House of Commons Speech |issue = 22 November 1990 |publisher = [[Hansard]]  HC [181/445-53] |via = Margaret Thatcher Foundation |date = 22 November 1990 |quote = People on all levels of income are better off than they were in 1979. The hon. Gentleman is saying that he would rather that the poor were poorer, provided that the rich were less rich. That way one will never create the wealth for better social services, as we have. What a policy. Yes, he would rather have the poor poorer, provided that the rich were less rich. That is the Liberal policy. }}</ref> It has also been used in the UK to refer to [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|the 2010\u20132015 coalition]] and [[Second Cameron ministry|2015\u20132016]] governments led by [[David Cameron]].<ref>Coalition:\n\n*{{cite news |title = Tories Make the Rich Richer and the Poor Poorer |url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/kamran-hussain/david-cameron-austerity_b_4310611.html |work = The Huffington Post UK |language = en-GB }}\n*{{cite news |last1 = Waugh |first1 = Rob |title = Rich have become richer thanks to 'austerity' politics - but poor lose out |url = http://metro.co.uk/2014/11/16/rich-have-become-richer-thanks-to-austerity-politics-but-poor-lose-out-4950177/ |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = Metro |date = 16 November 2014 }}\n2015\u2013present:\n\n*{{cite news |title = Labour: soaring levels of homelessness under Cameron mean more children facing Christmas on streets |url = http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/14160723.Labour__soaring_levels_of_homelessness_under_Cameron_mean_more_children_facing_Christmas_on_streets/ |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = Herald Scotland }}\n*{{cite news |title = Cameron tries to soothe MPs ahead of challenging year for party management |url = http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/01/cameron-tries-to-soothe-mps-ahead-of-difficult-year-for-party-management/ |accessdate = 2 May 2016 |work = Coffee House |date = 2 January 2016 |language = en-US }}</ref>\n\n==Other uses==\nIn [[statistics]], the phrase \"the rich get richer\" is often used as an informal description of the behavior of [[Chinese restaurant process]]es and other [[preferential attachment]] processes, where the probability of the next outcome in a series taking on a particular value is proportional to the number of outcomes already having that particular value.  This is useful for modeling many real-world processes that are akin to \"popularity contests\", where the popularity of a particular choice causes new participants to adopt the same choice (which can lead to the outsized influence of the first few participants).\n\n===Markets with social influence===\nProduct recommendations and information about past purchases have been shown to influence consumers choices significantly whether it is for music, movie, book, technological, and other type of products. Social influence often induces a rich-get-richer phenomenon ([[Matthew effect]]) where popular products tend to become even more popular.<ref name=\"altszyler2017\">{{cite journal | url= http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0180040 | title= Transient dynamics in trial-offer markets with social influence: Trade-offs between appeal and quality. |author1= Altszyler, E |author2=Berbeglia, F.| author3= Berbeglia, G. |author4=Van Hentenryck, P. | journal=  PLoS ONE | year=2017 |volume=12|issue=7 | doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0180040 | page=e0180040|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1280040A | pmc=5528888 | pmid=28746334}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Economic inequality}}\n* [[Capital accumulation]]\t\n* [[Internal contradictions of capital accumulation]]\n* [[Matthew effect]]\n* [[Preferential attachment]]\n* [[Socialism for the rich and capitalism for the poor]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Hayes |first1 = Brian |title = Follow the Money |journal = American Scientist |volume = 90 |issue = 5 |pages = 400 |year = 2002 |doi = 10.1511/2002.5.400 }} &mdash; Hayes analyzes several computer models of market economies, applying statistical mechanics to questions in economic theory in the same way that it is applied in [[computational fluid dynamics]], concluding that \"If some mechanism like that of the yard-sale model is truly at work, then markets might very well be free and fair, and the playing field perfectly level, and yet the outcome would almost surely be that the rich get richer and the poor get poorer.\"\n* {{cite book |author = Rieman, J. |year = 1979 |title = The Rich Get Rich and The Poor Get Poorer |publisher = Wiley |location = New York }}\n* {{cite book |title = The Screwing of the Average Man &mdash; How The Rich Get Richer and You Get Poorer |author = David Hapgood |publisher = Bantom Books |year = 1974 |isbn = 0-553-12913-9 |url-access = registration |url = https://archive.org/details/screwingofavera00bant }}\n* {{cite book |title = Why the rich get richer and the poor get poorer |author = Rolf R Mantel |publisher = Victoria, prov. de Buenos Aires |location = Universidad de San Andr\u00e9s |year = 1995 |id = OCLC 44260846 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Ispolatov |first1 = S. |last2 = Krapivsky |first2 = P.L. |last3 = Redner |first3 = S. |title = Wealth distributions in asset exchange models |journal = The European Physical Journal B |volume = 2 |issue = 2 |pages = 267\u201376 |year = 1998 |doi = 10.1007/s100510050249 |arxiv = 1006.4595 |bibcode = 1998EPJB....2..267I }} &mdash; Ispolatov, Krapivsky, and Redner analyze the wealth distributions that occur under a variety of exchange rules in a system of economically interacting people.\n* {{cite journal |pages = 301\u20139 |issue = 1 |volume = 45 |last1 = Chung |year = 1990 |doi = 10.2307/2328824 |journal = The Journal of Finance |first1 = Kee H. |last2 = Cox |first2 = Raymond A. K. |title = Patterns of Productivity in the Finance Literature: A Study of the Bibliometric Distributions |jstor = 2328824 }} &mdash; Chung and Cox analyze a bibliometric regularity in finance literature, relating [[Lotka's law|Lotka's law of scientific productivity]] to the maxim that \"the rich get richer and the poor get poorer\", and equating it to the maxim that \"success breeds success\".\n\n{{Extreme wealth}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rich Get Richer And The Poor Get Poorer}}\n[[Category:Wealth concentration]]\n[[Category:Economic inequality]]\n[[Category:American political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Adages]]\n[[Category:Economics catchphrases]]\n[[Category:British political phrases]]\n[[Category:Quotations from literature]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in the 19th century]]\n", "name_user": "La coince", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_rich_get_richer_and_the_poor_get_poorer"}
