10cukari\u010dki Stankom]]\n| years1 = 1982\u20131985\n| clubs1 = [[Red Star Belgrade]]\n| caps1 = 2\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1985\u20131990\n| clubs2 = [[Tacoma Stars (MISL)|Tacoma Stars]] (indoor)\n| caps2 = 247\n| goals2 = 209\n| years3 = 1990\n| clubs3 = [[R\u00e5sl\u00e4tts SK]]\n| caps3 =\n| goals3 =\n| years4 = 1990\u20131992\n| clubs4 = [[St. Louis Storm]] (indoor)\n| caps4 = 91\n| goals4 = 113\n| years5 = 1992\u20131994\n| clubs5 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| caps5 = 46\n| goals5 = 4\n| years6 = 1994\u20131995\n| clubs6 = [[San Jose Grizzlies]] (indoor)\n| caps6 = 32\n| goals6 = 67\n| years7 = 1994\u20131995\n| clubs7 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]\n| caps7 = 40\n| goals7 = 5\n| years8 = 1996\u20132000\n| clubs8 = [[Sporting Kansas City|Kansas City Wizards]]\n| caps8 = 145\n| goals8 = 50\n| years9 = 2001\n| clubs9 = [[Miami Fusion]]\n| caps9 = 24\n| goals9 = 8\n| years10 = 2002\u20132005\n| clubs10 = [[Kansas City Wizards]]\n| caps10 = 73\n| goals10 = 21\n| totalcaps = 330 \n| totalgoals = 88 \n| nationalyears1 = 1996\u20132001\n| nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 28\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| manageryears1 = 2006\n| managerclubs1 = [[Chivas USA]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2007\u20132009\n| managerclubs2 = [[Chivas USA]]\n| manageryears3 = 2010\n| managerclubs3 = [[Toronto FC]]\n| manageryears4 = 2014\u20132015\n| managerclubs4 = [[Sacramento Republic FC|Sacramento Republic]]\n| manageryears5 = 2017\n| managerclubs5 = [[Saint Louis FC]]\n| manageryears6 = 2018\u2013\n| managerclubs6 = [[Seattle Sounders FC]] (assistant)\n| medaltemplates = \n{{Medal|Country|{{Flagu|United States}}}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]|[[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup|1998]]}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|Soccer]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Predrag Radosavljevi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr-Cyrl|\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0440\u0430\u0433 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0432\u0459\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b}}; born June 24, 1963), better known by the nickname '''Preki''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|r|\u025b|k|i}}), is a [[Serbian American|Serbian-American]] former [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. international]] [[association football|soccer]] manager. He previously managed [[Sacramento Republic FC]] and [[Saint Louis FC]] in the [[USL Championship|United Soccer League]].  He also previously coached in [[Major League Soccer]] with [[Toronto FC]] and [[Chivas USA]].\n\nDuring his playing career he played for English clubs [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], and was an 'MLS original' upon the formation of [[Major League Soccer]] in 1996, playing for the [[Kansas City Wizards]] (now known as Sporting Kansas City) and [[Miami Fusion]]. He is the only two-time winner of the MLS MVP award, now known as the [[Landon Donovan MVP Award]], and represented the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. He was elected to the American [[National Soccer Hall of Fame]] in 2010.\n\nIn 2015 Preki left his managing role at [[Sacramento Republic FC]] by mutual consent. It was thought that he had landed the [[Leicester City FC]] job, but it was given to [[Claudio Ranieri]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/everton-fc-cult-figure-preki-9618350 |title=Everton FC cult figure Preki tipped for remarkable Premier League return |accessdate=2015-07-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304062130/http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/everton-fc-cult-figure-preki-9618350 |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Professional===\nBorn in [[Socialist Republic of Serbia|Serbia]], Preki played briefly for [[Red Star Belgrade]] in the old [[Yugoslav First League]] after coming from [[FK \u010cukari\u010dki Stankom]] where he played in their youth team.<ref>[http://www.pageflip-flap.com/read?r=tOqdiQoYQtfej3f5jl Monografija: 85 godina SD \u010cukari\u010dki] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425080415/http://www.pageflip-flap.com/read?r=tOqdiQoYQtfej3f5jl |date=April 25, 2012 }} (page 91&92) {{in lang|sr}}</ref> In the summer of 1985, the [[Tacoma Stars (MISL)|Tacoma Stars]] head coach [[Bob McNab]] spotted Preki at an indoor tournament in [[Belgrade]]. McNab signed Preki.<ref>''`SECRET' SLAV ADDS SOCK TO STARS' SOCCER OFFENSE'' THE SEATTLE TIMES \u2013 Thursday, October 24, 1985</ref> He played five seasons for the Stars. During those years, he was a three-time First Team All Star, the 1988 and 1989 All Star Game MVP, led the league in assists in 1988 and scoring in 1989 and was the 1989 MISL MVP. During the summer of 1989, Preki began to consider becoming a U.S. citizen and returning to the outdoor game in order to make himself eligible for the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. national team]].<ref>''PREKI EYES RAISE, U.S. CITIZENSHIP \u2013 WORLD CUP BERTH IN MIND'' Seattle Post-Intelligencer \u2013 Wednesday, September 13, 1989</ref> He played one season for [[R\u00e5sl\u00e4tts SK]] in Sweden in 1990.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.raslattsk.se/03Historia.aspx |title= R\u00e5sl\u00e4tts SK \u2013 Historia |format= |work= |accessdate=January 25, 2011}}</ref> The Stars released Preki in July 1990 as part of a salary reduction move.<ref>''Tacoma cuts Preki, 5 more to pare costs'' San Diego Union (CA) \u2013 Thursday, July 5, 1990</ref> In August, he signed with the [[St. Louis Storm]].<ref>''STARS' PREKI SIGNS WITH ST. LOUIS'' THE SEATTLE TIMES \u2013 Monday, August 13, 1990</ref> He played two seasons in St. Louis before being bought by [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] manager [[Howard Kendall]] for a fee of \u00a3100,000 in the summer of 1992 following a trial. He made 53 appearances for the Blues, 28 of those as a substitute. In June 1994, Preki signed with the [[San Jose Grizzlies]] of the [[Continental Indoor Soccer League]] where he rejoined Bob McNab from his Tacoma days.<ref>''CONTINENTAL INDOOR SOCCER LEAGUE'' USA TODAY (Arlington, VA) \u2013 Tuesday, June 7, 1994</ref> He played eight games, scoring sixteen goals, before returning to England in August 1994 to play for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. On July 5, 1995, the Grizzlies purchased Preki's contract from Portsmouth.<ref>''GRIZZLIES ACQUIRE TOP INDOOR PLAYER'' San Jose Mercury News (CA) \u2013 Thursday, July 6, 1995</ref> He was the CISL's second leading scorer and league MVP.<ref>[http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1995.html#CISL The Year in American Soccer \u2013 1995] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226150651/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1995.html |date=February 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Major League Soccer===\nPreki resumed outdoor play beginning with MLS's inaugural season in 1996 when he joined the [[Kansas City Wiz]], renamed the Wizards after the 1996 season. The league [[1996 MLS Inaugural Allocations#Kansas City Wiz|allocated]] him to the Wiz on February 6, 1996.<ref>''Transactions'' The Kansas City Star \u2013 Tuesday, February 6, 1996</ref> He played every season of his MLS playing career for the Wizards, except for one season with the [[Miami Fusion]] in 2001. After the Fusion were contracted, the Wizards reacquired Preki in the [[2002 MLS Dispersal Draft]], but only after every other team in the league had passed on selecting him. Preki is the only player to have won the [[Landon Donovan MVP Award|MLS MVP Award]] and the [[MLS Golden Boot|MLS Scoring Champion Award]] (now respectively known as the Landon Donovan MVP Award and the MLS Golden Boot) twice, winning in 1997 and 2003, and is also the current all-time league leader in points scored (270 on 79 goals and 112 assists, plus another 25 points on 10 goals and 5 assists in the playoffs). He won the 2000 [[MLS Cup]] with the Wizards. Preki retired following the 2005 season, scoring a goal in the last minute of his final game with Kansas City. He was named to the [[MLS All-Time Best XI]] after the season, and was 42 years old when he played his final competitive game.<ref>[http://web.mlsnet.com/players/bio.jsp?team=mls&player=radosavljevic_p&playerId=rad474619&statType=career MLS Player Stats] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501181728/http://web.mlsnet.com/players/bio.jsp?team=mls&player=radosavljevic_p&playerId=rad474619&statType=career |date=May 1, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===International===\nOriginally from Yugoslavia, Preki was living and working in the US in 1985 but when he was offered a spot on the [[United States men's national soccer team|American national team]] he applied for U.S. citizenship which was granted on October 25, 1996.<ref>https://ussoccerplayers.com/player/preki</ref> He made his debut for the United States on November 3, 1996 against [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]] at the age of 33, making him one of the oldest players to make an international debut. Preki played a total of 28 games for the U.S., scoring four goals, one of them to beat [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] at the [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup|1998 Gold Cup]]. Two of those games, including one against his native [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|Yugoslavia]] (now [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]]), came in the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. He made his last appearance for the national team in a 2\u20130 loss away to Costa Rica in World Cup qualifying on September 5, 2001.<ref>[http://web.mlsnet.com/t120/load.jsp?section=about&content=coaches About Coaches: Preki Radosavljevic, Head Coach] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522013613/http://web.mlsnet.com/t120/load.jsp?section=about&content=coaches |date=May 22, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible expanded\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1 || December 21, 1996 || [[San Salvador]], El Salvador || {{fb|GUA}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 2\u20132 || [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|1998 World Cup Qualifying]]\n|-\n| 2 || November 16, 1997 || [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]] || {{fb|SLV}} || '''4'''\u20132 || 4-2 || [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|1998 World Cup Qualifying]]\n|-\n| 3 || February 7, 1998 || [[Oakland, California]] || {{fb|CRC}} || '''2'''\u20131 || 2\u20131 || [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]\n|-\n| 4 || February 10, 1998 || [[Los Angeles, California]] || {{fb|BRA}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 1\u20130 || [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]\n|}\n\n==Coaching career==\nUpon the appointment of [[Bob Bradley]] as the United States national team manager, Preki was promoted as head coach of Chivas USA for the 2007 [[Major League Soccer]] season.<ref name=hiredatchivas>{{cite news|title=Preki replaces Bradley as Chivas USA coach|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=400382&cc=5901|accessdate=January 14, 2013|newspaper=ESPN Soccernet|date=January 17, 2007|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nPreki left Chivas \"by mutual consent\" on November 12, 2009, following Chivas' failure to progress to the latter stages of the MLS playoffs.<ref name=departfromchivas>{{cite news|title=Chivas USA, Preki part ways|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=697912&sec=mls&cc=5901|accessdate=January 14, 2013|newspaper=ESPN Soccernet|date=November 12, 2009}}</ref> He became head coach of [[Toronto FC]] on November 19, 2009.<ref name=hiredbytoronto>[http://www.torontosun.com/sports/soccer/2009/11/19/11804886-sun.html TFC set to name Preki new head coach]</ref> However, Preki didn't last the 2010 MLS season with Toronto, being fired along with General Manager [[Mo Johnston]] on September 14, 2010.<ref name=firedbytoronto>{{cite news|last=Wolstat|first=Ryan|title=Axed TFC coach Preki fires back|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/soccer/2010/09/15/15366226.html|accessdate=January 14, 2013|newspaper=Toronto Sun|date=September 15, 2010|agency=QMI Agency}}</ref> Under Preki, Toronto qualified for the [[2010-11 CONCACAF Champions League]] after winning the [[2010 Canadian Championship]].\n\nOn July 15, 2013, after nearly three years out of coaching, Preki was named head coach of the [[United Soccer League|USL Professional Division]] (now United Soccer League) expansion [[Sacramento Republic FC]] in advance of their inaugural 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insider.sacprosoccer.com/page/press-release |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609190442/http://insider.sacprosoccer.com/page/press-release |archivedate=June 9, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He won the USL Pro Championship game in September 2014 with the club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Republic FC Claims USL PRO Championship|url=http://uslpro.uslsoccer.com/home/839638.html|publisher=USL Pro|accessdate=September 28, 2014|date=September 27, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018101005/http://uslpro.uslsoccer.com/home/839638.html|archivedate=October 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 8, 2015, Preki announced his resignation from his post to take up a coaching role in the United Kingdom.\n\nOn October 12, 2016, USL club [[Saint Louis FC]] introduced Preki as its coach for the upcoming 2017 season. On November 20, 2017, [[Saint Louis FC]] relieved Preki of his coaching duties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lyons |first=Joe |date=October 12, 2016 |title=St. Louis FC introduces Preki as its new coach |url=http://www.stltoday.com/sports/soccer/st-louis-fc-introduces-preki-as-its-new-coach/article_4f0433b9-e844-586a-ae10-ef6a4470fa5c.html |newspaper=Saint Louis Post-Dispatch |location=Saint Louis, Missouri |access-date=December 11, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118010559/http://www.stltoday.com/sports/soccer/st-louis-fc-introduces-preki-as-its-new-coach/article_4f0433b9-e844-586a-ae10-ef6a4470fa5c.html |archivedate=November 18, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, Preki was hired as an assistant coach to [[Brian Schmetzer]] with the [[Seattle Sounders]].\n\n==Coaching record==\n\n{{updated|November 19, 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"| From\n!rowspan=\"2\"| To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\n|-\n!G\n!W\n!L\n!T\n!GF\n!GA\n!GD\n!Win %\n|-\n| [[Chivas USA]]\n|January 17, 2007<ref name=hiredatchivas/>\n| November 12, 2009<ref name=departfromchivas/>\n{{WDL|107|41|36|30|for=132|against=125|diff=yes}}\n|-\n| [[Toronto FC]]\n| November 19, 2009<ref name=hiredbytoronto/>\n| September 14, 2010<ref name=firedbytoronto/>\n{{WDL|32|11|11|10|for=30|against=31|diff=yes}}\n|-\n| [[Sacramento Republic FC|Sacramento Republic]]\n| July 15, 2013\n| July 8, 2015\n{{WDL|53|33|15|5|for=108|against=60|diff=yes}}\n|-\n| [[Saint Louis FC]]\n| October 12, 2016\n| November 19, 2017\n{{WDL|35|11|15|9|for=41|against=53|diff=yes}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| Total\n{{WDLtot|227|96|77|54|for=311|against=269|diff=yes}}\n|}\n\n=='''Awards'''==\n\n==[[Tacoma Stars]]==\n[[Major Indoor Soccer League]] Runners-Up: 1986-87\n\n==Kansas City Wizards==\n[[MLS Cup]]: 2000 <ref>{{cite web |title=2000 MLS Cup |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/history/2000-mls-cup |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[Supporters' Shield]]: 2000 <ref>{{cite web |title=Supporters' Shield |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supporters%27_Shield |website=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[US Open Cup]]: 2004 <ref>{{cite web |title=2004 U.S. Open Cup |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/history/2004-open-cup |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Individual==\n[[Major Indoor Soccer League]] MVP: 1988-89<ref>{{cite web |title=Major Indoor Soccer League |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_(1978%E2%80%931992)#Awards |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[Major Indoor Soccer League]] Scoring Champion: 1988-89 <ref>{{cite web |title=Major Arena Soccer League |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_(1978%E2%80%931992)#Awards |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia}}</ref>\n[[Major Indoor Soccer League]] Pass Master (Most Assists): 1987-88, 1988-89 <ref>{{cite web |title=Major Arena Soccer League |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_(1978%E2%80%931992)#Awards |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[1989 Major Indoor Soccer League All-Star Game]] MVP: 1989 <ref>{{cite web |title=1989 Major Indoor Soccer League All-Star Game |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_All-Star_Game |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[Landon Donovan MVP Award]](2): 1997, 2003 <ref>{{cite web |title=Sporting Legends- Preki |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/sportinglegends/preki |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[MLS Golden Boot]]: 1997, 2003 <ref>{{cite web |title=MLS Golden Boot |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLS_Golden_Boot |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\nIndoor Soccer Hall of Fame- Class of 2013 <ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Famers |url=https://www.indoorsoccerhall.com/hall-of-famers |website=Indoor Soccer Hall of Fame |publisher=Soccer Shift |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Preki}}\n* [http://www.ussoccerplayers.com/players/preki/ Preki profile at United States National Soccer Players]\n* [http://www.nasljerseys.com/MISL/Players/P/Preki.htm MISL stats]\n* {{NFT player|id=11454}}\n\n{{Seattle Sounders FC squad}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title       = United States squads\n| bg          = white\n| fg          = #002868\n| bordercolor = #BF0A30\n| list1 =\n{{United States squad 1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{United States squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=navy\n|list1=\n{{MLS All-Star 